<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, May 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Train Derailment Triggers Explosion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EUNICE, La. (AP) -- Thousands of people were ordered to evacuate their homes
and businesses on Saturday after a Union Pacific freight train loaded with
hazardous chemicals derailed and exploded, sending fireballs into the sky. No
injuries were reported. Officials said the worst chemicals in the wreckage were
methyl chloride, acrylic acid, toluene diisocyanate, and dichloropropane. Large
amounts can cause convulsions, coma, and death. Lower amounts can cause
staggering, blurred or double vision, dizziness, and fatigue, among other
things.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wendy's Suspect Faces Charges
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A man arrested in the execution slayings of five people at a
Wendy's was a fugitive free on $3,500 bail after a string of armed robberies at
fast-food restaurants, authorities said Saturday. Prosecutors had requested a
bail of $100,000 for John ''Benji'' Taylor, but the judge released him last
summer. The 36-year-old suspect and an alleged accomplice were to be arraigned
Sunday for killing five Wendy's employees and wounding two others. Their heads
wrapped in plastic, they were bound, gagged and shot execution-style.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ulster Unionists Endorse Joint Gov't
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's major Protestant party
voted Saturday to resume power-sharing alongside the IRA-linked Sinn Fein. The
grassroots council of the Ulster Unionist party decided by a 459-403 vote to
revive on Tuesday the joint government that began operating in December but was
suspended because the Irish Republican Army refused to make any disarmament
commitments. The IRA broke the impasse three weeks ago, promising to begin
disarming if power-sharing resumed. Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams, speaking in
New York, called the vote the ''right decision.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Criticizes Bush Nuclear Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. (AP) -- Al Gore criticized George W. Bush's proposal to cut
America's nuclear arsenal whether or not Russia does the same, telling West
Point cadets on Saturday that it ''will create instability and undermine our
security.'' Bush last week proposed reducing the U.S. nuclear stockpile to its
''lowest possible number consistent with our national security,'' even without
Russia making cuts. The Texas governor paired the cuts with a broad national
security review that must include a missile defense system. He also opposes a
treaty that bans worldwide tests of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tornadoes Cause Damage in Arkansas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LEACHVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Thunderstorms and tornadoes damaged homes and downed
trees and power lines in northern Arkansas Saturday, injuring at least one
person. Five people died in traffic accidents. A tornado touched down near
Leachville, in the northeast corner of Arkansas, Arkansas State Police said. At
least one person was injured, authorities said. The heavy rain also prompted
flood warnings and stranded several campers, canoeists and kayakers along the
rapidly-flowing Buffalo National River. National Park Service employees rescued
one kayaker from a tree at Ponca.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peers Honor 'Peanuts' Creator Schulz
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The National Cartoonists Society and guests honored Charles
M. Schulz, the late creator of Charlie Brown and Snoopy, with The Milton Caniff
Lifetime Achievement Award. His widow, Jeannie, accepted the organization's
highest honor during the black-tie event on Saturday night. ''Peanuts'' made its
official debut on Oct. 2, 1950. The daily tales of the ''little round-headed
kid'' and his pals eventually ran in more than 2,600 newspapers, reaching
millions of readers in 75 countries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Stars Bury Avalanche 3-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Sergei Zubov and Mike Modano scored on the power play in the
first period and the Dallas Stars built a three-goal lead, then withstood a late
rally by Colorado for a 3-2 victory in Game 7 of the Western Conference finals
on Saturday. The defending champions will open the finals Tuesday night in New
Jersey. The Devils overcame a 3-1 deficit to beat Philadelphia in the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Cut Pacers' Series Lead to 2-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks withstood the losses of Marcus Camby and
Patrick Ewing and beat the Indiana Pacers 98-95 on Saturday in Game 3 of the
Eastern Conference finals. Latrell Sprewell broke out of a series-long slump and
scored 32 points and Allan Houston won his matchup with Reggie Miller and scored
28 as the Knicks cut the Pacers' lead to 2-1 in the best-of-seven series. Game 4
is Monday. It was another chapter of adversity overcome for a Knicks team that
always seems to play its best when things look their worst.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
