<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Whooping Crane Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- A whooping crane whose birth was the
first documented in the U.S. wild in 60 years has died, apparently
after being attacked by a bobcat.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission said the
bird was found Thursday in 2 inches of water with signs that it had
been chewed and partially eaten, ''conditions associated with
bobcat predation.''
</P>
<P>
   The chick, which was born in March, was hailed by biologists as
the first solid sign of success in a 7-year-old program to
reintroduce the rare birds to the wild in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Excitement over the birth, however, was mitigated by the fact
that the chick's chances for surviving to adulthood were slim since
it was likely to be eaten by a predator.
</P>
<P>
   The chick was about to enter one of the most dangerous phases of
its life -- learning to fly -- when it was attacked. Fledglings who
leave their parents' nest are vulnerable to predation.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists had fitted the chick with a transmitter to track its
movements and progress, said Steve Nesbitt, project leader for the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The whooping crane was near extinction by 1938, when only two
small flocks remained, one in Canada and the other in Louisiana. A
storm wiped out all but six of the Louisiana birds, and none laid
eggs again.
</P>
<P>
   The last survivor of that flock died in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have been working since the late 1960s to raise the
birds in captivity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 0234 </TRAILER>
