<DOCNO> APW20000528.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 08:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Everest Climber Took Hour Longer  </HEADLINE>
By BINAJ GURUBACHARYA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) -- A Sherpa guide who set a new record for
the fastest ascent of Mount Everest said Sunday that he took an
hour longer to climb the world's highest peak than had been
reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Babu Chhiri, 34, scaled the 29,035-foot mountain to its summit
on May 21 through icy winds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I climbed the mountain in 16 hours and 56 minutes and not 15
hours and 56 minutes as reported due to communication problems
between the base camp and me,'' Chhiri told reporters when he
arrived in Katmandu.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the extra hour he said he took, Chhiri still broke the
record for the fastest climb, set two years ago by Kaji Sherpa, who
climbed Everest in 20 hours and 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Most climbers take two to four days to cover the distance from
the base camp at 17,500 feet to the summit, depending on the
weather.
</P>
<P>
   This was Chhiri's 10th successful summit of Everest. Only two
others have achieved this feat. In 1995, he became the first
climber to scale Everest twice in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Nepalese Sherpas, Chhiri climbs without bottled
oxygen, even though air pressure is low, making breathing
strenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have made the climb in about 14 hours if it had not
been for the heavy wind and snow,'' Chhiri said.
</P>
<P>
   Chhiri's brother, Dawa, had scaled the mountain earlier and
waited at the summit to welcome him.
</P>
<P>
   At the summit, the two brothers spent only about 10 minutes
before making a hasty retreat to lower camps.
</P>
<P>
   Most climbers retreat within a few minutes of scaling the peak,
with its high winds, freezing temperatures, rapid weather changes
and lack of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Chhiri's May 21 ascent came a year after he set a record by
camping for 21 hours on the peak.
</P>
<P>
   The Sherpas, who live at the foot of the Himalayas, are known as
''Tigers of the Snows.'' Renowned for their mountaineering skills
and stamina, many work as guides and porters for tourists in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first recorded climb of Everest in 1953 by Sir Edmund
Hillary and Sherpa Tenzing Norgay, more than 800 people have
conquered the tallest peak. Some 180 people have died on its
slopes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 0808 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crew Saved From Japan Tanker Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- All 34 crew members of an Indian oil tanker that
caught fire in the East China Sea were found Sunday by a Chinese
rescue boat, the Japanese coast guard said.
</P>
<P>
   The 26,450-ton Pratibha Yamuna went up in flames Saturday night,
about 340 miles west of the southern Japanese island of Amami
Oshima. The crew, all Indian, had been feared missing.
</P>
<P>
   Amami Oshima is part of a chain of smaller islands stretching
southwest of Kagoshima, which is 615 miles southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The coast guard received a fax from China's Rescue Coordination
Center in Beijing saying a Chinese boat rescued the entire crew of
the Pratibha Yamuna, said coast guard spokesman Shinya Nakawatase.
</P>
<P>
   The tanker was not carrying any oil at the time of the accident,
and no oil leakage has been found.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was brought under control, and the tanker, which will
be taken by Chinese tug boat to Shanghai, was not in any danger of
sinking, said Coast Guard official Shigenobu Tanaka.
</P>
<P>
   The tanker, which departed from Singapore, was en route to China
after stopping in South Korea, he said. The coast guard was
investigating the cause of the fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
