<HEADLINE> Eritrea Reports 'Senseless' Attack  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) -- Eritrea reported fighting Sunday on all
fronts on the eve of peace talks with its neighbor, accusing
Ethiopia of ''senseless destruction'' in the bombing of a civilian
power plant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new front opened in Eritrea's humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ongoing fighting near the central city of Mendefera threatens to
uproot 200,000 people, U.N. Eritrea coordinator Simon Nhongo
warned, dramatically intensifying the civilian flight from a
2-week-old offensive that already has sent an estimated one-seventh
of the nation's people fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks, buses and vans commandeered by the government poured
into the grounds of a school 22 miles south of the capital Sunday,
disgorging hundreds of women and children, each carrying a bulging
bag or two of their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Boys clambered off the high-paneled, open-backed trucks first.
Parcels, babies and women -- clasping their skirts to protect their
modesty -- followed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have only these pieces of clothes,'' said 70-year-old
Bisrat Berhe. Her son was fighting on the front, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The primary school grounds -- deserted the day before -- held at
least 18,000 people Sunday morning, with 6,000 more arrivals
expected by day's end.
</P>
<P>
   The civilians fled ahead of Ethiopia's artillery and
aircraft-backed pursuit of Eritrean forces retreating from the two
countries' disputed border.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea said last week that the fighting already had uprooted
555,000 of its 4 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Punished by the offensive, Eritrea agreed to withdraw from all
disputed territory and to talks due to start Monday in Algiers on
resolving the neighbors' 2-year-old war over their ill-delineated
border in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, however, says it will keep up its attack until it is
satisfied Eritrea has indeed withdrawn from all land Ethiopia
claims as its own.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Ethiopian warplanes bombed a nearly completed
power plant near the port city of Massawa, Eritrea's Foreign
Ministry said, calling the attack ''vandalism and senseless
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia late Saturday accused Eritrea of launching an offensive
from one of the points from which it had promised to withdraw,
saying the countries' artillery gunners exchanged fire at the
eastern town of Bure.
</P>
<P>
   In Asmara, Eritrea's capital, presidential spokesman Yemane
Gebremeskel reported fighting on all fronts Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was also the ninth anniversary overthrow of the military
regime that once ruled Ethiopia, which in 1991 still included the
province of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of Ethiopians rallied in their capital,
Addis Ababa, celebrating both the anniversary and victories in the
ongoing offensive in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the 1930s guerrilla war against Italian dictator
Benito Mussolini's forces stood alongside armed units in a central
square, watching warplanes away from the front perform aerobatic
rolls overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ''The invading Eritrean forces have been demolished,'' President
Negasso Ghidada told the elated crowd, listing cities and
territories retaken after being captured by Eritrea earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
