<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teens Throw Stones at Israel Border  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese and Palestinian teens threw
stones at an Israeli army border post and one attempted to climb
the frontier fence Sunday, drawing shots that caused at least three
slight injuries amid growing tension after Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   A boy was hit in the back by what appeared to be a rubber bullet
fired by the Israelis at the border some 50 miles south of Beirut.
A man in his 20s, said to be a supporter of the Lebanese Amal
guerrilla group, was carried away with a minor wound in his right
leg after more shots rang out.
</P>
<P>
   About four soldiers emerged from the post later, pointed their
rifles toward the crowd and fired up to five shots, injuring one
more person in the leg. Witnesses said a fourth person was hurt but
that could not be independently determined.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army would not immediately comment on the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Lebanese, guerrillas and civilians, have been
converging on the border fence at Kfar Kila since Israeli troops
hastily withdrew Wednesday from Lebanon after an 18-year
occupation. Guerrillas quickly moved in to fill the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   People have come to look across at Israel, a country many have
never seen, or to vent their anger. Others have tossed bottles and
firebombs, prompting Israeli soldiers to fire shots in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's trouble at the border began when about 10 teen-age boys
from a crowd that sometimes swelled to about 500 ran back and forth
at the fence, collecting stones to launch at a building that once
served as an Israeli border crossing before Israel slammed shut the
gates upon its army's pullout from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Some stones hit the roof or bounced back on a metal fence
surrounding the two-story building amid shouts of ''We're coming.
We're coming'' or ''Barak tell the truth. Are you scum or not?''
The Israeli prime minister is Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are our enemies and are still in Palestine,'' said
Youssef al-Mamoun, a 20-year-old Palestinian, as he headed toward
the fence with a stone in each hand.
</P>
<P>
   About four busloads of Palestinian refugees had come down to the
border fence to join the Lebanese. A Palestinian flag flew among
many Lebanese guerrilla and national flags.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmoud Ahmed, 13, criticized stone-throwers. ''They are not
acting civilized. I am not with Israel but they should not be
throwing stones. They got out of our land,'' he said, adding that
his concern was ''maybe some Israeli soldier will ... shoot
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   The injured boy was identified by his relatives as 15-year-old
Fadi Nemeh, a Palestinian. Blood trickled from his back as he
walked away but his injury appeared to be light.
</P>
<P>
   Without U.N. peacekeepers and Lebanese troops, who are yet to
deploy on the border, tension has been growing in the past few
days. Israel complained to the U.N. peacekeeping command, which
sent a patrol on Saturday to keep people away but the U.N. patrol
later left.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers have been keeping people away from their side
of the fence and Barak said Sunday that the army will only fire in
self defense or for rescue missions on the tense border.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah leader Sheik Hassan Nasrallah said in an interview
Saturday that the demonstrations at the border were to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, the Israelis have been showering us with bombs and
shells for more than 20 years. Let them tolerate this,'' he said
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel Sunday, Barak told his Cabinet that more than 90
percent of the Chebaa farms border area will not be evacuated
because it is not in Lebanese territory, according to U.N. maps.
Lebanon has called for a complete evacuation of the area and
Hezbollah has warned it will continue attacks unless troops leave
the farms.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the army completed an evacuation of two outposts in
the Chebaa farms region, north of Israel's border.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office also denied media reports that Hezbollah and the
Israeli army had reached a temporary cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army continued round-the-clock construction to
finish fortifications along the international border, setting up
fences, putting up warning signs and establishing roads, at some
points only a few yards from Israeli communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1032 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0025 </DOCNO>
