<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sitting All Day Can Be Bad for Back  </HEADLINE>
By IRA DREYFUSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- White collar life can be bad for the back.
Sitting all day at a desk, not working out, and then maybe golfing
on the weekend is just asking for trouble, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sitting position maximizes pressure on the lumbar discs in
the lower back, and that leads to back problems in adults,'' said
Dr. Vijay Vad of the Hospital for Special Surgery in New York City.
''Unfortunately, because of the twisting motion of the back, golf
falls into the high risk category for low back problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have to suffer through a day at the office when they
are not golfing make their problems worse by not doing exercises to
strengthen the muscles of the lower torso, said Vad, who works with
touring pros in the Professional Golfers Association and the
Association of Tennis Professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the discs do not circulate blood
through veins and arteries, but get their nutrients through fluid
circulation that comes as the back moves, said Dr. Vert Mooney, an
orthopedic surgeon at the University of California, San Diego.
Sitting still can't be counted on to provide enough fluid
circulation, he said. The lack of nutrient movement in, and waste
movement out, reduces the discs' ability to maintain healthy
strength, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Office workers would be better off thinking of sitting as an
athletic activity, in which they put the weight of their upper body
on their lower back -- maybe then, they'd prepare for it, Vad said.
''One of the things you can't afford not to do is simple stretching
exercises for the lower back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most cases of low back pain go away within a few weeks, but the
problem affects many people. Over 2 million people seek care each
year for lower back pain, said Vad and a fellow doctor at the
Manhattan hospital, Leon Root.
</P>
<P>
   Root and Vad say 15 minutes of abdominal, back, hamstring and
gluteal exercise a day can help people avoid or reduce the risk of
back problems. Among the exercises are leg extensions and partial
situps. Other exercises also can be valuable, and these include
weight training 2 or 3 times a week, Mooney said.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise can help people who have injured their backs avoid
doing it again, the doctors said. Studies of first-time back pain
patients in Australia found that people who did not exercise
regularly after their injury had an 80 percent chance of needing
more medical care, compared with only 20 percent of exercisers,
Mooney said.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend athletes, especially golfers, face additional problems.
The twisting motion of a golf swing is just what people with back
problems don't need, the doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   And golfers with poor swings make things even worse for
themselves, Vad said. A bad swing relies mostly on the upper body,
and twists at the waist, while a good one draws power from the legs
up, he said. In a good swing, the lower back just transmits power
instead of initiating it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden starts, stops and twists of tennis also can cause
problems, but they are less common, the doctors said. ''Tennis is
(a sport) of moderate risk,'' Vad said.
</P>
<P>
   Root also warns that bowling can be bad for the back of those
who are not experienced bowlers. The unevenness of the throw,
caused by the heavy weight that results from having the ball in one
hand, can lead to lower back problems, he said. However, horseback
riding seems safe enough, as does baseball, unless the player tries
to put too much into the swing, Root said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1201 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ficus for Congress: A campaign rooted in satire   </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A team of candidates for Congress, deeply
rooted in the environment, is trying to strike a blow this election
year against the power of incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger in one Pennsylvania campaign traveled the
district on a ''listening tour.'' In Georgia, a candidate felt at
home at the grand opening of a greenhouse. A Texas candidate sports
a cowboy hat, while one in South Carolina posed outside Bob Jones
University.
</P>
<P>
   And a candidate in New Jersey had no comment after the state
Board of Elections refused to accept its petition for a spot on the
ballot under the slogan, ''Because a Potted Plant Can Do No Harm.''
</P>
<P>
   If 1992 was the ''year of the woman'' in congressional
elections, some people want 2000 to be the year of the ficus.
Mobilized by satirist Michael Moore, whose documentary ''Roger &AMP;
Me'' assailed General Motors Corp. for closing its plant in Flint,
Mich., political skeptics across the country have signed up to seek
write-in votes for trees from the family ficus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing this because the American people no longer show up
to vote,'' Moore said during a campaign appearance in April for the
tree challenging Rep. Rodney Frelinghuysen, R-N.J. ''The majority
of people feel they have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ficus trees are being offered as candidates in three House
districts in Alabama, one in Arkansas, two in California, one in
Illinois, one in New Jersey, one in New York, two in North
Carolina, one in Ohio, two in Pennsylvania, one in South Carolina,
three in Texas, four in Virginia and one in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   One senator, Republican Craig Thomas of Wyoming, has ficus
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 House ficus campaigns, 21 target Republicans. Another
is against Rep. Virgil Goode of Virginia, who switched his
affiliation in January from Democrat to independent. The other is
for the seat being vacated by retiring Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the evident political slant, the campaign was designed
to challenge veterans in both parties who draw little or no
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Voters have stopped going to the polls because today's
politicians -- Republicans and Democrats -- all stand for pretty much
the same things,'' reads the first plank in the ficus platform.
''The ficus campaign has recaptured voters' imagination in a way no
other candidate can, by offering a real choice: politician or
potted plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign volunteers say they see the effort as a lark, but one
with a message.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Cook of State College, Pa., said she was ''really
disappointed'' when she learned that Republican Rep. John Peterson
of Pennsylvania had no Democratic opposition this year. So she and
her husband Sean volunteered to host a ficus campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that people need to know that even when an incumbent
is running unopposed, they do have a choice,'' said Cook, who works
at Penn State University.
</P>
<P>
   Lorne Wolfe, an associate professor of biology at Georgia
Southern University, is helping run the ficus campaign against
Republican Rep. Jack Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a plant biologist,'' he said, ''I was glad to see that
(Moore) chose a plant to represent an alternative for the voting
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Seeman, who is running the ficus campaign in Ohio against
Republican Rep. Ralph Regula, said his campaign theory is simple:
''Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it would be better to have a potted plant
represent us in Congress, but I certainly don't see how it could be
worse,'' said Seeman, field representative for a national radio
syndicator.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents targeted by the ficus have responded in the spirit of
the campaign. Kingston pledged to ''keep my feet firmly planted in
the issues'' affecting his district in Georgia. Frelinghuysen said
his ficus opponent is ''truly green when it comes to politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The ficus campaign is taking place largely on the Internet,
through a home page set up by Moore. The campaign last week sent
supporters an e-mail asking them to film footage of their ficus in
campaign mode, for use on Moore's cable television show, ''The
Awful Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   One supporter posted a message on the web site wondering, ''What
will happen if one of the Ficus actually wins?''
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem, replied a fellow ficus fan, who said he watches
C-SPAN and notices members talking among themselves while a
colleague is addressing the House.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least the ficus will be quiet while others have the
floor,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ficus2000.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
