<HEADLINE> A new approach to getting rid of old tires  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GORMLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Environmental activism and business
development would be combined under a new proposal to rid New York
state of the growing, silent threat of old tire dumps.
</P>
<P>
   A bill making its way through the state Legislature would
promote the development of stable, private-sector tire recyclers by
providing them with state grants and other government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a company that already manufactures asphalt for
road surfaces could receive a grant to buy equipment that would
allow recycled tires to be incorporated into its paving materials,
the bill's sponsors say.
</P>
<P>
   Those businesses would be fueled by old tires in individual
sites in Suffolk, Saratoga, Chenango, Oswego, Erie and Chautauqua
counties. Sites with 100,000 or more tires each are found in
Ulster, Columbia, Rensselaer, Albany, Wyoming and Cattaraugus
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Most other counties also have smaller scrap tire stockpiles,
said Assemblywoman Audrey Hochberg, a Westchester Democrat and
chairwoman of the Assembly Solid Waste Management Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it is estimated that between 25 million and 40 million
old tires have been dumped, mostly illegally, in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mosquitos breed in scrap tries at an unbelievable rate,''
Hochberg said. ''Mosquitos, the only known source for transmission
of the West Nile Virus, reproduce at a rate up to 4,000 times
greater in scrap tire piles than in their natural environment ...
and there is an inability for pesticides to penetrate the tire
stockpile.''
</P>
<P>
   The virus has killed seven people in New York City and infected
1,900 people in Queens alone, state and federal health officials
said. The water in scrap tires prompts the fast breeding of
mosquitos while sheltering them from natural predators.
</P>
<P>
   ''The recycling of scrap tires has not kept pace with the
production of new scrap tires,'' said state Sen. Carl Marcellino, a
Long Island Republican and chairman of the Senate's committee on
the environment. ''The resulting waste tire piles create two
potential hazards -- tire fires and mosquito infestation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tire fires are a particular environmental hazard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a tire fire in the picturesque Greene County town of
Catskill created a canopy of thick, toxic smoke for months. The
acrid smoke from this and seven other major tire fires in New York
since 1994 have threatened air and water. The fires can burn for as
long as a year and toxins generated by the blazes can seep into the
water supply for years afterward.
</P>
<P>
   David Higby of Environmental Advocates said shredded tires can
be recycled in ''any number'' of new products, if the proper
assistance is provided to businesses to make it worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Higby is also part of a statewide committee of tire industry
leaders and environmentalists that helped create the legislation
now before the Legislature That 2-year-old partnership is why he
believes the measure has a strong shot at becoming law in these
last few weeks of the 2000 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation takes us forward towards a comprehensive plan
to manage both the stream of new scrap tires and the clean-up of
the scrap tire dumps that plague our state,'' Marcellino said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
