<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State to require safety course for all 'Jet Ski' riders  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- People thinking about hitting the water on
''Jet Skis'' in New York will have to hit the books first under new
guidelines from the state parks department.
</P>
<P>
   The rules will require anyone who wants to use a personal
watercraft, more popularly known by the trademark ''Jet Ski'' name,
pass a daylong boating safety course taught by a certified
instructor.
</P>
<P>
   The office cited an increasing number of fatal accidents
involving personal watercraft in implementing the guidelines last
week. The Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation was
mandated to implement the guidelines by the state Legislature,
which passed a broader law to require the move two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Jacangelo, director of Marine, Coastal and Legislative
Program Development for the office, said it has taken two years to
develop the education program since it will involve so many people.
He said there are 50,000 personal watercraft in New York and
estimated there are twice as many personal watercraft operators.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York will have the largest education program for personal
watercraft operators in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fruition of the law pleased lawmakers, including Assemblyman
Harvey Weisenberg. Weisenberg, a Long Island Democrat who is also a
lifeguard, sponsored the measure in the Assembly when it passed in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very strongly that this legislation is going to save
people's lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Weisenberg also cautioned the guidelines will only be as
effective as their enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Parks officials say that while personal watercraft comprise only
10 percent of vessels registered in New York, they are involved in
30 percent of waterway accidents. The office says inexperience and
lack of training are the main cause of personal watercraft
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines take effect incrementally; this year, any person
aged 10 to 19 will have to take the test, as minors have had to do
for more than 30 years. Children younger than 10 are not allowed to
operate personal watercrafts.
</P>
<P>
   By 2001, anyone under 23 will take the test; by 2002, it is 27;
by 2003, it is 31 and by 2004, potential riders of all ages will
have to spend a day in a classroom before getting their day in the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   The courses will be offered through the parks department, but
others can apply to become teachers. The classes will be free, but
a permanent certificate stating people passed the course will cost
adults $10, which will go toward funding the program. The fee will
be waived for children.
</P>
<P>
   The department estimates private instructors will charge between
$30 and $80 for classes and ''well more'' than 100,000 people will
have taken a safety course through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   People who are caught operating personal watercraft without
passing the class will be subject to a series of fines. A
first-time offender faces a fine of between $25 and $100 and up to
seven days in jail. A person caught twice within two years faces a
fine up between $100 and $200 and up to 15 days in jail. A person
caught three times within two years faces a fine of between $200
and $500 and up to 30 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ''Year by year, our recreational boating report gives clear and
convincing information that personal watercraft accidents occur
because of the inexperience of the operator,'' Jacangelo said. ''We
know we can overcome inexperience through education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
