<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Guerrillas Focus on Farms  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEBAA, Lebanon (AP) -- A fertile patch of rolling hills once
prized most by farmers and cigarette smugglers on mules could be
the rallying point for reigniting a battle that has taken two
decades to quell.
</P>
<P>
   The Chebaa farms, a strip of land tucked into the western
foothills of Mount Hermon between Lebanon and the Israeli-annexed
Golan Heights, remains disputed territory in a region trying to
redefine borders that all sides can tolerate. Guerrillas whose
roadside bombings and rockets finally wore out Israel's will to
stay in south Lebanon have warned Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
to be wary as long as his forces are there.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian and Lebanese governments also want Israeli troops to
turn the Chebaa farms over to Lebanon as part of their pullout from
the country's south, completed last week after 22 years of
operating in or occupying the area. But Israel has said it won the
land from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war and is not obligated to
give it to Lebanon -- a position accepted by the United Nations as
it takes on the task of confirming a complete Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah leader Sheik Hassan Nasrallah did not say whether a
continued Israeli presence in Chebaa farms would be enough on its
own to prompt an attack by his guerrillas, but he has called on
Barak to remove his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ''The farms of Chebaa will return to Lebanon. The days will
prove that,'' Nasrallah told 30,000 jubilant supporters at a rally
last week in the former occupied zone in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Fertile ground for barley, fruits and vegetables, the area's
location at the corner where Syria, Israel and Lebanon meet also
has made it an ancient route for smuggling. In recent decades, it
was known as a path for smuggled cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   As U.N. envoy Terje Roed-Larsen has noted, Lebanon and Syria,
which politically and militarily dominates its smaller neighbor,
haven't designated an international border at Chebaa. To residents
of Chebaa village, the agricultural land on its outskirts is
Lebanese -- many say their families have deeds to property there.
</P>
<P>
   There are no accurate figures on the size of the Chebaa farms,
but Lebanese press reports said 13 farms stretch about 15 miles
long and five miles wide. They run along Mount Hermon's western
foothills between Chebaa and the village of Kfar Chouba to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's withdrawal from the surrounding area has allowed
Lebanese close enough to see into Chebaa farms through a
barbed-wire fence. Though many came to take a look in the heady
days following Israel's withdrawal and to congratulate each other
on what is viewed as a guerrilla triumph over Israel, some
residents said the occupation isn't quite over.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can congratulate me when we're 100 percent free,'' said
Raed Hashem, a 36-year-old goat herder who said his family owns 11
acres in the Chebaa farms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
