<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Has Chance To Show Strength  </HEADLINE>
By EARLEEN FISHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- With the departure of the last Israeli
occupation troops, the Lebanese government has its first chance in
decades to show authority throughout its own country and, perhaps,
even become a partner instead of a pawn in regional politics.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it takes the opportunity -- not to mention the land
vacated last week by Israel -- depends upon how, or even whether, it
can cut through a complicated knot of internal and external
realities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are on the edge of a new era. It can be something
completely positive for Lebanon, and it can be something completely
dark for Lebanon,'' said Gebran Tueni, publisher of An-Nahar, the
most independent newspaper in Lebanon. ''Everything is moving.
That's why everything is so dangerous. That's why we are really on
a turning point where anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The unquestioned power in this nation is and will remain Syria,
the authoritarian regime that wraps around Lebanon's northern and
eastern borders. Syrian soldiers have been stationed in Lebanon
since 1976, nominally as a deterrent but also as a participant in
the civil war that raged from 1975 until 1990. They now number
about 30,000. In the last few years, the number of Syrian laborers
injected into Lebanon, population 4 million, has swelled to as many
as a million during peak demand.
</P>
<P>
   But something unique happened last week when Hezbollah
guerrillas -- the Shiite Muslim spearhead whose attacks weakened
Israeli resolve to remain in Lebanon -- moved into border villages
vacated by Israel's army and its quick-to-evaporate militia allies
of the Christian-led South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah's backing comes from Syria and Iran, but the
guerrillas who fought the Israelis and took over the border zone
when they left were Lebanese, saluted even by the Lebanese
government as liberators acting in the national interest. Lebanon
has seen scores of militias seize territory over the years, but
rarely, if ever, have any of them showed so much discipline after
victory.
</P>
<P>
   There have been spots of looting in Christian villages dotting
Shiite-majority south Lebanon since the Israelis pulled out last
Wednesday, but -- despite the killing of a Christian man by a
guerrilla on Sunday -- there have been none of the bloody vengeance
attacks and massacres that were an integral part of territorial
turnovers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Such restraint could give Hezbollah a chance to increase the
seven seats it now holds in the 128-member Parliament in elections
expected later this summer. But under Lebanon's complicated
electoral system, which apportions seats geographically and then by
a variety of religious sects within each district, neither
Hezbollah nor any other single group can aspire to a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Lebanon's future has a clear set of destinations,
but the timetable is uncertain. One goal is peace talks between
Syria and Israel, leading to a treaty under which Syria recovers
the Golan Heights it lost to Israel in the 1967 war. That would
clear the path for a Lebanese-Israeli peace treaty, which can
happen only after the Syrian treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need the Syrians,'' said An-Nahar commentator Sarkis Naoum,
voicing a sentiment grudgingly shared by Lebanese from many social
and sectarian backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Syrians are a stabilizing factor, and they are also a
destructive factor,'' Naoum said. ''It's in our interest to
continue the cooperation with the Syrians. But after the Israeli
withdrawal, the Syrians have no excuse to stay in Lebanon
militarily. Politically, they will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Lebanese government has moved tentatively
in returning to the southern tenth of the country vacated by
Israel. About 400 Lebanese policemen have been sent to the area,
but they constitute little more than a living flag if they are not
reinforced quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, deployed just north of the
Israeli-controlled zone since 1978, has started mobile patrols
along the border while awaiting the arrival of more troops to swell
its current force of 4,500 peacekeepers to as many as 7,900.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians, meanwhile, have a more peaceful way of using
Lebanon to pressure Israel than supporting the guerrillas who
lobbed rockets into the Jewish state. Syria could use the precedent
Israel set -- fulfilling a U.N. resolution by withdrawing from
Lebanon -- to campaign for implementation of other resolutions
calling for withdrawal from Syria's occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a new tool in the Syrian negotiations,'' said Talal
Salman, publisher of As-Safir, a newspaper with close ties to
Damascus. ''Why did Israel implement U.N. resolutions in Lebanon
but not in Syria?''
</P>
<P>
   He echoed the views of others here that the international
community, including the United States, cannot allow Israel to pick
and choose which U.N. resolutions it will honor. A 1978 resolution
called for Israel to get out of Lebanon, but earlier ones in 1967
and 1973 called for Israel to return all war-won lands -- which
include the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Earleen Fisher, the AP's chief of Middle East
Services since 1992, is based in Cairo and has spent 16 of the past
23 years in the Middle East. Her previous posts include Beirut
1980-83 and Tel Aviv 1983-85.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1343 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Kelly's Widow Hands Out Awards  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Patricia Ward Kelly said she didn't know who
Gene Kelly was when she met the ''Singin' in the Rain'' star in
1985, but when he later asked her to help him write his
autobiography, ''We worked together and we fell in love.''
</P>
<P>
   He was 73, she was 26. The actor's widow told a Gene Kelly
Awards ceremony in his hometown Saturday that as they worked on the
book, Kelly told her about Pittsburgh -- memories of air filled with
coal dust, dance classes at a synagogue and arguing philosophy and
politics in local taverns.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said his childhood in Pittsburgh was the greatest time in
his life, almost idyllic -- nothing ever compared to it,'' Mrs.
Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gene Kelly Awards are presented by the Pittsburgh Civil
Light Opera for excellence in high school musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will always be a very special place in his memory and now a
very special place in mine,'' she said of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1351 </TRAILER>
