<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mac attack: For Somers Point entrepreneur, image is everything  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERS POINT, N.J. (AP) -- Bubba Mac is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He's up there on the wall mural, cooking up barbecued ribs for
B.B. King, Muddy Waters and Stevie Ray Vaughan. He's over there on
the American Gothic-style T-shirts, holding a guitar by the neck,
standing alongside a smiling alligator.
</P>
<P>
   He's there on the front door of Bubba Mac Shack, his shaggy
Jerry Garcia-like visage etched into the glass.
</P>
<P>
   He's on the ersatz $1 ''Bubba Bucks'' that come attached to the
Shack's menu, right under the ''You kill it, we grill it''
inscription.
</P>
<P>
   His face is even on the rubber hand-stamp that is used to show
who has paid the cover charge.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the Jersey shore's most eccentric new club -- his
real name: Herbert Birch Jr. -- is no egotist. He knows his own
quirky image gives the club its cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a marketing thing,'' he says. ''Hey, it worked for
Kentucky Fried Chicken. It worked for Jerry Garcia.'' Besides:
''It's distinctive, it's easy to remember and it means I'll never
HAVE to get a haircut.''
</P>
<P>
   But the image is only an image.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the shoulder-length blond hair, the Grizzly Adams beard
and the wire-rimmed eyeglasses is a creative, well-financed
businessman who knows what sells -- and has enough backing not to
worry if it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a patent attorney, Birch started his career as an
accountant. In 1976, he founded a management consulting firm, Birch
&AMP; Davis Holdings Inc., in Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which provided health care management and
consulting services to governments, blossomed into a $70
million-a-year juggernaut with 900 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, he and his partner sold out in a
multimillion-dollar deal that made Birch rich. One of the first
things he did was build a bonfire, burning all his suits and ties
at once.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am no longer a suit,'' he says, wearing an open-necked
shirt, baggy pants and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he began making plans for a restaurant club combining two
of his loves -- New Orleans-style cuisine and the blues.
</P>
<P>
   He picked the Jersey shore, having spent summers in Ocean City
as child.
</P>
<P>
   Birch, his son Mac, and two other partners settled on a
14-year-old waterfront building on Bay Avenue that has been the
site of several failed restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Renaming it Bubba Mac Shack (''barbecue, seafood and blues''
reads the sign), they gutted the place and started over, aiming to
convert it into a restaurant with the best live blues music
available -- or a blues club whose menu really cooks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted a place that was upscale but down-home, a place with
a kind of split personality. It's like a casual day at the office:
You can get funky but still be treated with a certain level of
class,'' Birch says.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an eclectic hybrid of a place that offers free
lessons in swing dancing two nights a week; three stages for live
music; a second-floor deck called the Lizard Lounge, just for
sunbathing; a menu that includes crawfish etouffee, shrimp creole
and oyster po' boys; and a Sunday brunch featuring a seven-person
gospel choir, free copies of The New York Times and all the Bloody
Marys you can drink, for $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the Bubba Mac Blues Band, an eight-man ensemble
that performs three times a week, featuring -- you guessed it --
Bubba Mac himself on guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba Mac Shack opened in March and has been a huge hit, despite
breaking ranks with the other bars along Bay Avenue, which cater
almost exclusively to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's done a tremendous amount of business this spring, which
is shocking because there's just not that many people around,''
said Randy Scarborough, who owns the building.
</P>
<P>
   This may be only the beginning. Birch says he hopes to build 10
similar Shacks over the next 10 years, all on the water.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll never leave the water. If you can't get there on the
inland waterway, we don't want to be there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There are other deals in the works, too. The Bubba Mac Blues
Band has released an 11-song CD, titled ''Road Kill.'' Birch also
plans a record label and a recording studio.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes they all succeed, but they don't have to. After all, he
says: ''I'm not underfinanced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
