<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rehnquist Tells Grads To Enjoy Life  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government's highest-ranking judge
warned new law school graduates Sunday not to devote too much time
to their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, offering ''a few bits of
advice,'' said aspiring to greatness is fine. But he urged young
lawyers to ''develop a capacity to enjoy pastimes and occupations
that many can enjoy simultaneously -- love for another, being a good
parent to a child, service to your community.''
</P>
<P>
   In his commencement speech to George Washington University's
graduating law class, Rehnquist suggested that ''these other fruits
of life'' will loom large when ''each of you will undoubtedly look
back many years from now upon your lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that large law firms in big cities try to hire top
graduates, Rehnquist said high salaries and the chance to do
interesting work are the pluses.
</P>
<P>
   ''The drawbacks are the relentless demand for billable hours,
which may leave less time than one would like for a personal
life,'' according to a copy of his prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller law firms in smaller cities, the chief justice said,
''You will certainly receive a smaller salary. ... There will be
less novel litigation, but the chances that you will actually go to
court and try a case are probably much greater.
</P>
<P>
   ''You will have more time for your family, for civic activities
and hobbies and will be able to feel more a part of the community
in which you live.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist, 75, graduated from law school 48 years ago and served
as a Supreme Court law clerk before heading to Phoenix, where he
practiced law for 16 years. He has been a Supreme Court member
since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lawyers were not nearly as time-conscious then as they are
now,'' Rehnquist said. ''This meant that they probably earned less
money than they might have, but had a more enjoyable life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
