<HEADLINE> Portugal Has Changed Over 15 Years  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY HATTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- When President Clinton flies into Lisbon
for a three-day visit Tuesday, he will encounter a country that has
undergone deep changes since the last U.S. president paid a visit
15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan came in 1985, a time when Portugal had not yet
shaken off the legacy of Antonio Salazar's stifling 41-year
dictatorship. It also had not recovered from the decade of
political upheaval that followed Salazar's ouster in a 1974
army-led coup.
</P>
<P>
   But 1985 was a significant year for Portugal, a country of 9.9
million people on the southwestern edge of Europe that is slightly
smaller in size than the state of Indiana. That was the year
Portugal joined the European Union and embarked on a period of
fast-track economic growth driven by billions of dollars in EU
development funds from the bloc's wealthier member states.
</P>
<P>
   ''The modernization of Portuguese society has been far-reaching.
Above all, it has been extremely swift,'' University of Lisbon
sociologist Antonio Barreto said.
</P>
<P>
   By embracing EU participation, Portugal quickly shed its image
as one of Europe's stragglers. Annual average gross domestic
product per person has risen from about 50 percent of the EU
average to about 70 percent, or $10,900, over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal currently holds the rotating presidency of the EU.
Clinton is coming for an EU-U.S. summit in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbon, most of all, illustrates the deep changes. As Portugal
posted annual economic growth rates of up to 6 percent in the late
1980s -- among the highest rates in the world -- sleek glass-fronted
office blocks sprung up next to the city's centuries-old and ornate
stone buildings.
</P>
<P>
   A cosmopolitan city of recently-arrived European workers and
African immigrants who came after the 1974 coup, the capital clings
to seven hills overlooking the saucer-shaped bay by the mouth of
the River Tagus. A red suspension bridge across the bay is
reminiscent of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone has profited from the new wealth. Those who
could manage it moved from Portugal's poor rural interior to the
cities, and now 40 percent of the population resides in Lisbon and
Oporto, the second-largest city. The average monthly salary is
about $555, but some in the interior still live mainly from
subsistence farming or on the minimum wage of about $266.
</P>
<P>
   The country also lags behind its wealthier EU partners in
education. Of people ages 25 to 64, only 20 percent stayed in
school until they were 18, according to the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
   Development was stunted under Salazar. Under the slogan
''Proudly Alone,'' he shut out foreign influences with the help of
censorship. His feared secret police repressed any opposition. Many
people emigrated in the 1950s and '60s for a better life abroad,
creating large Portuguese communities in New Jersey, France and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar, resisting the wave of independence that swept Africa in
the 1960s, sent thousands of troops to perpetuate Portuguese rule
in its African territories: Angola, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, Cape
Verde, and Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
   Decolonization and democracy finally came after the dictatorship
was toppled by a group of disgruntled army captains. But the
withdrawal was abrupt and disastrous: Cut loose, the African
countries drifted into the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   After the army coup, the Communist Party and moderate
left-wingers struggled for dominance in Portugal. The prospect of a
communist regime alarmed the country's NATO allies, including the
United States, which has kept a major air base in the Azores
islands since 1946.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese became weary of those political battles and now
cherish their political stability. The center-right Social
Democratic Party governed for 10 years after 1985, and now the
moderate Socialist Party is in its second term.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Portuguese experience has demonstrated that peaceful,
democratic change and progress are possible,'' President Bush said
in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1408 </TRAILER>
