<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Other cities have role in pier inspections  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- While Philadelphia officials have maintained
it is not the city's responsibility to inspect piers such as the
one that collapsed May 18, spilling dozens of nightclub patrons
into the Delaware River, government does take a role in other
cities to make sure such piers are structurally sound.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse killed three young women who worked at the New
Jersey State Aquarium across the Delaware in Camden, N.J.:
25-year-old DeAnn White of Philadelphia, the aquarium's public
relations manager; Jean Ferraro, 27, of Cherry Hill, the marketing
manager; and Monica Rodriguez, 22, also of Cherry Hill, N.J., who
had just finished the first day as a special events assistant.
</P>
<P>
   A check of cities with waterfront development -- such as San
Francisco; Baltimore; Norfolk, Va., and San Diego -- indicates that
many local governments assume some responsibility for the
structures, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton, N.J., does not require inspections of waterfront
properties, but the South Jersey Port Corp., a quasi-state agency
that operates the cargo piers in Camden, conducts regular
inspections and was recently informed that about $6.35 million in
work is needed on their five piers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, the port has divers inspect piers at least once a
year, and every 18 months a contract to replace old and damaged
wooden pilings is bid out to private contractors. In Norfolk, the
city hires a private firm for underwater inspections of its 300
publicly owned piers.
</P>
<P>
   In Oakland, across the bay from San Francisco, the agency
overseeing the port does the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do all of the underwater work,'' Juan Valerio said of the
city's inner harbor. ''It's critical for us to have our own people
down there. We're mandated by our own liability insurance to do
this. Other ports don't.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the entire bayfront area is owned by the Port
of San Francisco, a state-created governmental agency. In general,
officials said, each pier is inspected underwater every two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a pretty good idea up and down the waterfront what the
conditions are,'' said Cliff Jarrard, chief engineer for the Port
of San Francisco. ''We know which are the stronger ones, which are
the weaker ones, and which are in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the city's piers were built in the 1920s, most to handle
cargo. While uses ranging from apartments to athletic clubs have
been proposed for them during the city's current waterfront
development boom, many would require structural changes underwater
for such uses, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd be very careful about a proposal on some facility that's
very old and in the past has been used to store cargo, and now
someone wants to put people on it,'' Jarrard said. The office
complex under construction at Pier One, for example, required
extensive underwater upgrading of the pier.
</P>
<P>
   The port recently ordered a permanent evacuation of three old
piers used for small offices after divers found the
steel-reinforced concrete pilings were damaged. The concrete had
eroded and the steel had rusted, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can look at them from above, and they look fine,'' Jarrard
said. ''You go below, and it's frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, Commissioner Ed McLaughlin of the city
Department of Licenses and Inspections has said the structure of
the property is the owner's responsibility, and it is the owner's
responsibility to correct any problems.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has not required pier owners and developers to
provide proof that they had inspected the structures but has now
asked the owners of the 180 piers on the Delaware River to submit
inspection reports from private engineering firms by the end of
June.
</P>
<P>
   The department and Philadelphia police are investigating the
collapse of Pier 34, and the district attorney's office Friday
announced plans to convene a grand jury to determine whether
criminal charges should be filed in connection with the accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-28-00 1409 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
