<HEADLINE> Ban on Palestinian Cities Lifted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Israeli army on Sunday lifted a ban on the
entry of Israelis and foreign tourists to three Palestinians cities
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The ban was imposed May 21 after a 2-year-old Israeli girl was
badly burned by a firebomb while riding in a car through the West
Bank city of Jericho. The child is still in intensive care a week
later, a hospital official said.
</P>
<P>
   The firebomb incident followed the worst clashes in years
between Israeli soldiers and Palestinian demonstrators calling for
the release of Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   After the firebombing, the Israeli army banned Israeli civilians
and foreign tourists from entering all Palestinian cities in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. The army cited security reasons, but
Palestinian security chief Jebril Rajoub said it was collective
punishment aimed at harming the Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the ban was lifted from the cities of Nablus, Jenin
and Qalqilya. It had already been lifted in Jericho.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it remains in force in Ramallah, Tulkarm, Bethlehem and
Hebron, except for the small part of Hebron still controlled by
Israel. It also continues in Gaza City and in Khan Yunis and Rafah,
also in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
