<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siblings separated by tragedy reunited 74 years later  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SCHNECKSVILLE, Pa. (AP) -- Irene Spitko was 8 years old on the
cold February day in 1926 when her 13-month-old brother was taken
away to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ran after him crying,'' said Spitko, who will turn 83 on
Monday. ''Many days didn't go by that I didn't wonder about him and
if he got a good home.''
</P>
<P>
   Her questions were answered Saturday, when the Reading woman was
reunited with her brother Jim Beatty, 74 years after tragedy pulled
their family apart.
</P>
<P>
   Murmuring ''after all these years,'' Jim Beatty fell into the
arms of his sister, crushing between them the bouquet of roses he
was carrying. Beatty and his wife, Dorothy, now live in Barnegat,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe it,'' Spitko said. ''My last memory of you was
of a strange lady carrying you out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The reunion of the two siblings at the Schnecksville home of
Arthur Spitko, Irene's son, happened after four years of research
by Beatty's son, John Beatty and his wife, Karen. The couple
started their search after Jim Beatty received his adoption papers
when his father died.
</P>
<P>
   The papers named Beatty's birth parents and said he was born in
Bethlehem. Beatty told his son he really wanted to see a photograph
of his birth mother, Erma Waters.
</P>
<P>
   John and Karen Beatty headed to Bethlehem to sift through county
records, church listings and newspaper archives for clues. In
census records from 1920, five years before Beatty was born, they
discovered Erma Waters had lived in Bethlehem with a son and
daughter. It seemed Beatty had a brother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a lot of detective work,'' the younger Beatty said.
''But things were beginning to fall into place like someone was
guiding us.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a few more trips to Bethlehem, but the couple found
Beatty's parents' marriage certificate. That led him to the name
Spitko, and searches through phone books finally led to his
long-lost sister.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was in shock,'' Spitko said. ''I start to cry every time I
think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two then made plans for their meeting Saturday, where the
brother and sister clung tightly to each other and marveled at the
coincidences.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a statistics teacher,'' said Jim Beatty, a math professor
at Burlington County Community College. ''What's the possibility of
this happening?''
</P>
<P>
   Spitko said she had tried to find her brother but was stopped
cold by the sealed adoption records.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every year it seemed less likely it would happen,'' Spitko
said. ''But I never gave up hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitko said she had told her own children about the adoption of
her brother only eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother had a baby out of wedlock and I didn't want anyone
to think badly of my mother,'' she said. ''I have nothing but good
memories of my mom. She was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitko's father had already been dead for five years when her
mother became pregnant. After Jim, then called Neal, was born, Erma
Waters discovered she was dying of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was sick and couldn't take care of a baby,'' Spitko said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after the adoption, her mother died and Spitko went
to live with her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Jim had been adopted by the Beatty family of Latrobe,
Westmoreland County, and grew up unaware he was adopted until he
was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just accepted it,'' he said. ''I never thought any more of
it. I had no idea I had any biological family at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The siblings also are hoping to be reunited with another sister,
Wilma, who went to live with relatives when their mother died. A
brother died in infancy.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Irene Spitko and Jim Beatty have a lifetime to
catch up on.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm so happy for my dad and his sister,'' John Beatty said.
''I'm just beaming from ear to ear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
