<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party To Leave Polish Coalition  </HEADLINE>
By BEATA PASEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- The junior party in Poland's center-right
governing coalition voted Sunday to withdraw its ministers, likely
spelling the demise of Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek's 2{-year-old
government.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy with Buzek's inability to control maverick lawmakers
from his own Solidarity bloc, the executive council of the Freedom
Union voted nearly unanimously for its five ministers to submit
their resignations Monday. They will remain in office in a
caretaker capacity until a new government is formed.
</P>
<P>
   The party held open the option of forming a new coalition with
Solidarity under different leadership. Buzek has repeatedly offered
to resign if that would keep the partners together.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means Buzek's weakened government will stay in
place until the two sides hold talks. At that point, the Freedom
Union could either join Solidarity in a new government or it could
ditch the coalition altogether, leaving Solidarity to try to get by
with a minority government. The Solidarity bloc controls 185 of the
460 seats in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
   Such a government would probably not be able to get the 2001
budget passed, though. According to the constitution, parliament
would then have to be dissolved and early elections held in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't exclude the possibility of renewing the coalition''
under a new prime minister, Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz,
who heads the small Freedom Union, said at the start of Sunday's
meeting. He called for ''fast, complete and conclusive'' talks with
Solidarity leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The market-oriented Freedom Union was unhappy with Buzek because
deputies from the splintered Solidarity bloc have voted against the
government's own economic reforms on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders consider the reforms crucial to prepare
Poland to join the European Union. But some Solidarity lawmakers
argue such reforms ignore the needs of the very workers and farmers
who helped the Solidarity labor movement bring down communism a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Government decisions were blocked in parliament in some
essential elements while decisions harmful for the country were
forced through,'' Balcerowicz said in explaining his party's loss
of confidence in Buzek.
</P>
<P>
   Bronislaw Komorowski, leader of a conservative Solidarity
faction, accused the Freedom Union of trying to save face in a
situation it provoked. He said negotiations on appointing new
ministers would be ''very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to keep the 2{-year-old coalition together, Solidarity
last week suggested a replacement for Buzek: central bank economist
Boguslaw Grabowski. Grabowski, who co-authored Solidarity's
economic program, supports fast privatization and restraints on
government spending -- views close to Balcerowicz's.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Union praised the choice, but complained that
Solidarity still had not done enough to address its concerns about
party discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Many Solidarity politicians want Balcerowicz to resign as deputy
prime minister and finance minister if Buzek goes. That condition
could prove unacceptable for the Freedom Union and force it out of
the coalition altogether.
</P>
<P>
   If new elections end up being called, Solidarity could face a
stiff challenge at the ballot box. According to recent polls, the
left-wing, ex-communist opposition enjoys at least a 10 percentage
point lead over the Solidarity bloc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
