<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Bomb Found in Verona, Italy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Some 20,000 people were briefly evacuated in Verona
and the city's train station and airport were closed for hours on
Sunday so explosives experts could defuse a half-ton bomb from
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb, dropped by U.S. forces during the war, was found
recently during digging at a construction site near the train
station in the northern city of 250,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Work to defuse the bomb began in the morning and was completed
by early evening, when residents were allowed to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuated from their homes as a precaution were those living
within a half-mile of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Flights flying in and out of Verona's Villafranca airport were
diverted to the northern city of Brescia. Trains were allowed to
pass through the station for only a half-hour in the afternoon
while work to defuse the bomb was briefly halted, said the Italian
news agency ANSA.
</P>
<P>
   Police patrolled neighborhoods to discourage any looters from
entering vacated homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
