<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritreans Flee Heavy Fleeing  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) -- Fighting raged Sunday between the Horn of
Africa's warring neighbors on the eve of peace talks -- opening a
new front in Eritrea's smoldering humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Infantry and artillery clashes in what's become the heaviest
fighting in the 2-year-old border war threaten to uproot 200,000
people around the central city of Mendefera, the United Nations
warned. The 2-week-old Ethiopian offensive already has sent nearly
one-seventh of Eritrea's people fleeing north, some into
neighboring Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks, buses and vans commandeered by the government poured
into the grounds of a school about 20 miles north of Mendefera,
disgorging hundreds of evacuees, mostly women and children, each
carrying a bulging, plastic bag or two of their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Boys clambered off the high-paneled, open-backed trucks first.
</P>
<P>
   Parcels, babies and women -- clasping their skirts to protect
their modesty -- followed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have only these pieces of clothes,'' said 70-year-old
Bisrat Berhe, pinching the hem of her skirt as she crouched under
the eaves of a primary school that in the past day had become home
to 18,000 Eritreans.
</P>
<P>
   At least 6,000 new arrivals were expected by day's end, said
Simon Nhongo, a U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea said last week that fighting already had dislodged
555,000 of its 4 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia's military now is pursuing the retreating adversary
miles deep into Eritrea -- putting its citizens into panicked flight
ahead of the advance.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly punished by the latest offensive, Eritrea agreed
last week to withdraw from all disputed territory and return to
talks set for Monday in Algeria on resolving the neighbors'
2-year-old war over their poorly delineated border.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has made plain its bargaining strategy for the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shall negotiate while we fight and we shall fight while we
negotiate,'' Prime Minister Meles Zenawai told African diplomats in
the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Ethiopian warplanes bombed a nearly completed
power plant near the port city of Massawa, Eritrea's Foreign
Ministry said, calling the attack ''vandalism and senseless
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia said the planes attacked a military installation, not a
power plant.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Ethiopia accused Eritreans on Sunday of shelling
its forces near one of the eastern towns from which they had
pledged to withdraw, Bure.
</P>
<P>
   In Addis Ababa, Ethiopians rallied by the hundreds of thousands
to celebrate the ninth anniversary of the overthrow of the military
regime that once ruled Ethiopia, which in 1991 still included the
then-province of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   The ralliers -- grizzled veterans of the guerrilla war against
Benito Mussolini's forces alongside young men in uniform -- had new
triumphs to celebrate as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''The invading Eritrean forces have been demolished!'' President
Negasso Ghidada told the elated crowd, listing towns and
territories retaken by the country's forces in past days.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of talks in this David-and-Goliath struggle, which
pits a country of 4 million -- Eritrea -- against one of 61.7 million
-- Ethiopia -- the vaunted Eritrean army seems, at least for the
moment, to have misplaced its slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   An army that successfully fought against the U.S.-backed
royalist regime of Haile Selassie and the Soviet-backed military
dictatorship of Mengistu Haile Mariam has conceded key towns in
western and central Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   By the most obvious measure -- lost territory -- Eritrea's army
has been dealt a sharp setback, though not yet enough of one,
Ethiopian military commanders say.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to show Eritrean forces were intact and spirited, the
Asmara government took reporters to the border town of Adi Keshi on
Saturday and showed them the bodies of at least 24 Ethiopian
soldiers killed in an unsuccessful three-day assault on an Eritrean
mountaintop position last week.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the state of his morale after Ethiopia's march across
large swaths of Eritrean territory, 24-year-old Alhuir Fessehaye
burst out in Italian, ''Cento!'' (roughly, ''100 percent!'') and
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Around Fessehaye were reminders of the carnage and costs of a
war often fought hand-to-hand.
</P>
<P>
   Slung around the necks of nearby soldiers were ''kushufs,''
tightly wound shawls of often brightly colored cloth that Eritrean
soldiers use as sleeping mats or -- if they're killed -- as burial
shrouds.
</P>
<P>
   Down the boulder-strewn mountainside were the bloated,
decomposing bodies of Ethiopian troops stretched behind jagged
outcroppings where they fell under Eritrean mortar and
automatic-rifle fire.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrean soldiers and an Ethiopian prisoner of war claimed the
Ethiopians had to be goaded by screaming commanders to advance up
the steep mountainside.
</P>
<P>
   Found next to the body of 19-year-old Belete Ketema from
Nazareth, Ethiopia, was his diary in broken English, its last entry
breaking off mid-sentence as it recounted an episode in his brief
life: ''...when I spent my time in the market, I saw how the person
specially there are around me''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby in the nearly deserted town of Adiquala, at least 25
people too young or too old to flee huddled under a bridge to wait
out the war.
</P>
<P>
   Roma Gebrekian, 67, contemplated her fate and her country's
while she waited for Eritrean soldiers to bring her bread and
water.
</P>
<P>
   ''This must have been a curse,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
