<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aviation visionary gets state, national recognition  </HEADLINE>
By JIM MEMMOTT
Rochester Democrat and Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMONDSPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- The best-selling T-shirt at the
Curtiss Museum just south of this Steuben County village has an
airplane on the front and the phrase ''Wilbur &AMP; Orville Who?'' on
the back.
</P>
<P>
   No offense is meant by the question, says Kirk W. House, the
museum director. It's just another way of suggesting that the
museum's namesake, Glenn Hammond Curtiss, was the equal of Wilbur
and Orville Wright, the guys who got aviation off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But life isn't always fair. Even though Curtiss made
extraordinary contributions to aeronautics at the beginning of this
century, the Hammondsport native doesn't always get the credit he's
due outside the village of less than 1,000 residents that calls
itself the Cradle of Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why House is pleased that Curtiss, who died in 1930,
has been selected by the state Department of Transportation as New
York's most significant contributor or contribution to aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Curtiss was named in connection with a program conducted by the
National Aviation Hall of Fame in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Already a member of the Hall of Fame, Curtiss will be in a
state-by-state honor roll that includes some individuals, some
events (memorable flights) and even some airports.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is one of the few greats,'' says Jean Lail, archivist at
the Hall of Fame. ''We're trying to get the word out on him. The
planes he made are still out there. He was an incredible man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Curtiss Museum gives support to Lail's assessment,
chronicling a life of extraordinary and diverse achievement. ''He
was into so many things, you can't stay with him,'' House says.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hammondsport on May 21, 1878, Curtiss stayed in school
through eighth grade. In 1892, he moved to Rochester to join his
mother and sister, who had gone there so his sister could attend
what is now the School for the Deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Curtiss first worked for the Eastman Dry Plate and Film Co.,
which would become the Eastman Kodak Co. He then took a job as a
bicycle messenger for Western Union.
</P>
<P>
   The job, or at least bicycle riding, changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''With an inborn love for the sheer physical sensation of rapid
motion, and endowed with long legs that were like a pair of
muscular pistons, Glenn Curtiss caught racing fever,'' writes C.R.
Roseberry in ''Glenn Curtiss: Pioneer of Flight,'' which was
published in 1972 and reprinted by Syracuse University Press in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't working or taking part in bicycle races, Curtiss
rode his bike from Rochester to Hammondsport and back, about 70
miles each way.
</P>
<P>
   Curtiss moved back to Hammondsport in 1896 and eventually took
over a bicycle shop. By 1901, he had built a motorcycle, the first
of many. The Curtiss museum has an exhibit on early motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   His creations quickly became faster and faster, and in 1907
Curtiss set a land-speed record of 136.36 mph on his motorcycle. By
this time, he was also beginning to catch up with the Wright
brothers, who had made their first flight on Dec. 17, 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Curtiss joined with Alexander Bell, inventor of the telephone,
and other investors to build the June Bug, a biplane powered by one
of Curtiss' lightweight V-8 engines. On July 4, 1908, Curtiss
piloted the June Bug in the first pre-announced, officially
observed flight in the United States. The Wright brothers had not
announced their flight beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The June Bug traveled a little over a mile, 20 or so feet above
the ground. Average speed: 39 mph.
</P>
<P>
   After the flight, Curtiss' life was a series of triumphs, though
House says it was not the aviator's nature to brag. ''He was a
private, quiet man,'' House says. ''He wasn't a real social type. .
. . But everyone described him as a kind man.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis received the first pilot's license in the United States
in 1911, and he designed the first plane to take off and land on
water.
</P>
<P>
   He also created the Curtiss ''Jenny,'' a World War I plane made
first in Hammondsport and then Buffalo. The success of the Jenny
made Curtiss a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he also became involved in real estate in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Early in July 1930, Curtiss was stricken with appendicitis while
on his way from Hammondsport to Rochester for a court hearing. An
appendectomy in Buffalo seemed to be successful, but a pulmonary
embolism, or blood clot, took his life on July 23, 1930. He was 52.
</P>
<P>
   ''After risking his life in every kind of vehicle, he died in
that way,'' House says.
</P>
<P>
   Curtiss is buried in the Pleasant Valley Cemetery just outside
the village of Hammondsport, close to where the June Bug made its
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's people here who have never heard of the Wright
brothers,'' says Jane Honeyman, who is in her 80s and has lived in
Hammondsport all her life. ''But everybody has heard of Glenn
Curtiss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-28-00 1615 </TRAILER>
