<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Parties Outline Differences  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Dissident members of Northern
Ireland's major Protestant party lost no time Sunday in declaring
their resistance to a soon-to-be restored administration that
includes members of the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<P>
   And Sinn Fein made clear it was not giving up its opposition to
Britain's plan for reforming the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the
province's police force, which many Catholics despise. Sinn Fein
says reform plans are inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists' narrow approval Saturday of a return to
power-sharing cleared the way for Britain to restore the
administrative authority it suspended in February over the refusal
of the outlawed Irish Republican Army to disarm. Power returns at
midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble barely managed to persuade
his badly divided party to give the IRA a chance to live up to its
unprecedented pledge three weeks ago to begin putting its weapons
''completely and verifiably beyond use'' if the new provincial
administration resumed.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Trimble warned the IRA that it must deliver on
its promise.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let there be absolutely no doubt that I and my colleagues will
hold the republicans to the promises they have made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein declined to speculate on when the IRA would begin to
reveal any of its secret weapons dumps to international inspectors
-- the most concrete commitment made in its May 6 disarmament
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble won with only 53 percent of the council vote. Many
Ulster Unionists oppose the 1998 Good Friday peace accord under
which the new Cabinet and Assembly were established in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important the voices of the 47 percent are heard,'' said
Jeffrey Donaldson, one of Trimble's strongest opponents within the
party. ''If we need to come back again to press for IRA disarmament
that's what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein deputy leader Martin McGuinness, who will return as
education minister, welcomed Trimble's success.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have waited for far too long to see an Ulster Unionist
leader and that section of the party who have told us consistently
that they are for the Good Friday Agreement face down the unionist
rejectionists who are out to destroy it,'' McGuinness told GMTV
television on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   McGuinness criticized the police reform plan put forward by
Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, as a
''pale shadow'' of recommendations made last September by a reform
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Britain had insisted that the police force be renamed as part of
a reform effort, although Protestant hard-liners objected
vehemently. Before the Ulster Unionist vote, Mandelson suggested
the RUC name might be retained in some form.
</P>
<P>
   In a further bid to help Trimble, he announced he would have the
final say on whether the British flag flew over government
buildings -- another sore point with the Protestants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1619 </TRAILER>
