<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiananmen Crackdown Commemorated  </HEADLINE>
By PRISCILLA CHEUNG
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Gathering to commemorate the Tiananmen Square
military crackdown, more than 1,000 activists marched in Hong Kong
Sunday and vowed to keep fighting until China becomes a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters chanted slogans and sang patriotic songs. They
marched under the blazing sun amid a sea of black-and-white
placards that said: ''Demand accountability for 6.4 massacre,'' and
''Don't forget June 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Several protesters carried a wooden dummy coffin during the
four-mile march to the downtown government headquarters to
commemorate the dead from the 1989 crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we're seeing momentous economic developments in China,
why aren't we also seeing the end of one-party rule?'' asked labor
unionist and independent lawmaker Leung Yiu-chung.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds, if not thousands, of people were killed when tanks and
troops descended on demonstrators at Tiananmen Square in Beijing in
the early hours of June 4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing officially regards the student-led demonstrations as an
attempt to overthrow the government. Hong Kong activists hold
frequent protests to demand that Beijing release all jailed
dissidents and reassess the 1989 demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said about 2,000 people attended the march Sunday,
although the crowd appeared slightly smaller. Police did not
immediately give their estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators said younger people should learn about the
importance of democracy in China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time erodes our memories. China has no hope unless the new
generation understands the importance of democracy,'' said Andrew
To, a veteran activist and a district councilor of the popular
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Mok Chin-to, 41, waved a 3-foot by 5-foot Taiwanese flag during
the march, which he said represents the hope of multiparty,
democratic elections on Chinese soil.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan elected Chen Shui-bian as president in March, generating
attacks from Beijing, which distrusts the former pro-independence
opposition leader. Beijing claims Taiwan as a renegade province to
be retaken eventually, by force if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Chinese dissidents asked the government to stop
condemning the 1989 democracy movement.
</P>
<P>
   In separate appeals, Wang Hongxue and Cheng Fan called on the
communist leadership to reappraise the seven weeks of massive
student-led protests that led up to the crackdown, the Hong
Kong-based Information Center of Human Rights and Democracy said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a million people in Hong Kong protested the crackdown
in 1989, and the issue remains a sensitive one in the territory.
Anti-China and anti-government protests have remained legal after
the handover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1627 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Leone Rebels Free UN Captives  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Rebels released 61 U.N. hostages
Sunday and U.N. officials said they expected 28 more to be freed
soon, a development which appeared to bring the four-week-old
hostage crisis nearly to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the 28 captives waiting to be transferred to northern
Liberia, U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said only 23 peacekeepers
were still being held out of some 500 U.N. personnel snatched last
month. The immediate fate of those 23, from India, remained
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the releases, fighting between rebels and pro-government
forces was reported over the weekend at the strategic crossroads of
Rogberi Junction, about 50 miles east of Freetown, Wimhurst said.
He had no further details.
</P>
<P>
   The 61 were flown to Liberia's capital of Monrovia in two
batches from eastern Sierra Leone, Wimhurst said. The 28 were
expected to be airlifted out late Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some 143 hostages were flown Friday and Saturday from Monrovia
to Freetown and hundreds more had trickled out in the weeks
earlier. The releases were negotiated by Liberia's President
Charles Taylor, the closest regional ally to the Revolutionary
United Front rebels, a secretive and isolated group notorious for
its diamond dealing and atrocities against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in military uniforms and clutching bottles of mineral
water, the hostages freed Sunday were relieved and joyful. Most
were in good physical condition, although some were being treated
for malaria, minor injuries and fatigue, Liberian medical officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very happy. I thought we were never going to reach this
place. Thank God we are here,'' said Zambian Lance Cpl. Elias
Mwanza, who suffered from a swollen jaw and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Mwanza said some of the captors had tormented the hostages while
others were more kind and promised not to kill them ''because we
are their African brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. Goma Justin, also Zambian, who had deep cuts on his foot
from stepping on broken glass, described his captivity as
''rough.''
</P>
<P>
   The 23 Indian peacekeepers continued to be held in
semi-captivity in the village of Quiver in the eastern Kailahun
district, Wimhurst said. They were apparently surrounded by rebels
and barred from leaving, but were allowed to keep their weapons,
according to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, West African heads of state were gathering for
weekend meetings in the Nigerian capital, Abuja, to discuss the
crisis in Sierra Leone. Informal talks were held Saturday and with
the main gathering was being held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have killed tens of thousands of people and
intentionally mutilated many more during the 8-year-old civil war.
The conflict reignited earlier this month when the Revolutionary
United Front rebels took the U.N. peacekeepers hostage and began
advancing toward Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a ragtag alliance of pro-government forces has tried
to push the rebels away from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Television News cameraman Miguel Gil Moreno de
Mora and Reuters correspondent Kurt Schork were killed Wednesday in
a rebel ambush. South African cameraman Mark Chisholm and Greek
photographer Yannis Behrakis suffered light injuries in the same
attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1643 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Reformist Parliament Opens  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Iran's reformist legislators said Sunday
that they intend to live up to their pledges they made to voters
who are anxious for greater social freedoms and economic stability.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were elected because we promised to pursue reforms. So, we
are intent on delivering the promises we have made,'' legislator
Soheila Jelowdarzadeh told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jelowdarzadeh, who won a Tehran seat in February's
legislative elections, conceded that reformists face an uphill
road.
</P>
<P>
   ''To meet popular demands, we need time to succeed. Opponents of
reforms will continue to resist and therefore we should still
expect political tension to continue in the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since the 1979 Islamic revolution that
the legislature has slipped out of the control of hard-liners, who
want no dilution of the clerical government's laws, many of them
unpopular due to their restrictions on personal freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ''So far, the reformists have not bargained against their
promises. I'm happy with that,'' said businessman Mohammad
Eskandari. ''Now I expect them to deliver their promises and pass
laws lifting the restrictions and protecting people's freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the state of Iran's ailing economy is a more pressing
matter than social freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation of 62 million, half of whom are under the age of 25,
Iranians are struggling with more than 20 percent unemployment and
high inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want a job. I need money to live. I expect the new Majlis to
help create jobs for the unemployed,'' said Mahmoud Lotfi, a young
man waiting with more than a hundred others for daily construction
jobs at a Tehran square, a sight repeated in many cities across
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the victory of the reformists, who won about
three-fourths of the 290 seats in the Majlis in the Feb. 18 polls,
their power struggle against the hard-liners is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   The Guardian Council, a supervisory body controlled by
conservatives, must approve new legislation before it becomes a
law.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-liners also control the judiciary, the broadcast
network and the security forces, and their chiefs are appointed by
Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who has the final
say in all matters.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, hard-liners have shut down 19 newspapers,
18 of them pro-reform, and jailed several reformist editors and
leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1645 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two arraigned in five murders at Wendy's  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two men accused of shooting seven people, five
of them fatally, in the holdup of a Queens fast-food restaurant
were formally charged on Sunday with multiple counts of murder,
attempted robbery and weapons possession.
</P>
<P>
   Queens Assistant District Attorney Greg Lasak described in
chilling detail how John Taylor, 36, and Craig Godineaux, 30,
allegedly bound and gagged their victims with duct tape, then
executed them one by one.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were marched single file into a big freezer box. They
were told to get on their knees, and they were each shot by the
defendants once in the head,'' Lasak said, his voice tremulous with
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Lasak told Queens Criminal Court Judge Michael Aloise that the
defendants had given videotaped statements admitting the shootings
at a Wendy's restaurant in Flushing last Wednesday night. In
addition, he said, witnesses picked them out of a police lineup,
and detectives seized money, a security tape from the restaurant's
camera and other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ''The evidence we have to tie these defendants to the case is
overwhelming,'' Lasak said.
</P>
<P>
   All seven people shot were employees of the restaurant. Five
were killed and two others survived with wounds, one of them by
playing dead until the bandits left.
</P>
<P>
   Lasak described the victims as ''seven hardworking people,
working in that restaurant that night... they were directed to lay
down on that floor. They were gagged over their mouths so they
could not scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Queens District Attorney Richard Brown has 120 days to decide
whether to seek the death penalty. Brown, who has twice before
recommended the death penalty, said he would use the time to
investigate, talk to victims' families and evaluate the defendants'
backgrounds, state of mind and mental capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision in regard to the death penalty is a decision I do
not take lightly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown refused to comment on media reports that Taylor had said,
''no witnesses,'' as his reason for shooting the workers after
taking $2,300. Most of the money, recovered at Taylor's house, was
in coins, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Aloise set the next hearing for June 26 and remanded the pair
without bail. Lasak asked for no bail, saying there was ''no
greater risk of flight'' than a potential death penalty.
Court-appointed attorneys John Youngblood and Heidi Segal reserved
bail requests.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor later was placed on suicide watch, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a short, heavyset man, stood during the proceeding,
staring straight ahead. Godineaux, tall and rangy, gazed at the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who appeared to be a friend of Godineaux walked in and
out of the courtroom, wearing a red sweater over her head. She
refused to identify herself to reporters, but as the defendants
were led away, she cried out, ''I love you, Craig,'' broke down in
sobs and wailed, ''Oh, God.''
</P>
<P>
   Each was charged with 10 counts of murder in the first degree
and 10 counts of murder in the second degree, plus the lesser
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Taylor was a fugitive who jumped bail in a previous
fast-food robbery and had a record stretching back to 1996, when he
was accused of trying to break into a safe at a McDonald's where he
was assistant manager, and sentenced to five years probation.
</P>
<P>
   In one week last June, he was linked to robberies or attempted
robberies at four fast-food businesses in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   The five workers killed at Wendy's were Ramon Nazario, 44; Anita
C. Smith, 23; Jeremy Ryan Mele, 18; Ali Ibadat, 40, and Jean
Auguste, 27, the night manager.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Castro, 23, shot through both cheeks, played dead, then
freed himself two hours later and called 911. He was released from
the hospital Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   JaQuione Johnson, 18, remained in critical condition after
surgery for a head wound at New York Hospital Medical Center in
Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-28-00 1645 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT Slug.  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
