<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein's Adams Talks to Grads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. (AP) -- With prospects brightening again for peace
in Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams told college
graduates that people are the same beneath their skin and that they
must start now to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the IRA-allied party also received an honorary
degree Sunday for the University of Massachusetts at Lowell, his
first from an American university.
</P>
<P>
   The commencement ceremony came one day after the Ulster Unionist
Party voted to rejoin the country's power-sharing government. Adams
welcomed Saturday's vote, which prompted the British government to
agree to restore home rule on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to develop a just society,'' he told the
audience of 6,500, including 1,700 graduates, in Lowell's Paul E.
Tsongas Arena. ''We have to keep focused on the prize because the
only way the bigots, rejectionists and naysayers can succeed is if
the rest of us give up ... and we are not giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain suspended the young government in February after the
Irish Republican Army refused to make any firm disarmament
commitments and Unionists threatened to walk out. The IRA broke the
deadlock three weeks ago, promising it would gradually place its
hidden weapons stockpiles ''verifiably and completely beyond use''
in cooperation with international arms inspectors if power-sharing
resumed first.
</P>
<P>
   Adams told students that any one of them could make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''We start from where we are,'' he said. ''You make a difference
wherever you happen to be. ... Below the skin we are all the
same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1727 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers won't take on organized labor in retirement payout limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- Wary of organized labor's clout, which
has hampered recent efforts to put controls on retirement payouts,
New Jersey lawmakers have pulled two bills that would cap how much
money state workers could receive for unused sick and vacation time
and quieted any rhetoric pushing such reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Christie Whitman, who made a failed attempt two years
ago to implement the caps as part of her ''smaller, smarter
government'' reforms, said she will try again to push through a
statewide limit on so-called ''golden parachute'' payouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Record of Hackensack reported in Sunday's editions that the
retirement payouts eventually will cost taxpayers at least $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Unions have argued they have the right to negotiate whatever
benefits they can, and over the past four year have derailed at
last a half-dozen efforts to control the payouts to teachers and
municipal employees.
</P>
<P>
   After a mobilization by the 162,000-member New Jersey Education
Association, the New Jersey School Administrators Association and
other groups, Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, on
March 30, 1998, withdrew a bill that would have limited payouts to
public employees and school board employees at $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill sponsored by state Sen. Leonard Connors, R-Ocean,
was pulled March 19.
</P>
<P>
   DiFranceso has denied he pulled the bill because he was afraid
of losing union support in a run for governor, saying he was
persuaded by arguments the groups presented in opposing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Joseph, an NJEA spokeswoman, said the benefits were
properly negotiated with bargaining representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the state to interfere in the collective bargaining
process undermines everything that the process is about,'' Joseph
told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   It would be ''ill-advised'' to attempt to take the benefit from
workers who negotiated in good faith, said Charles Wowkanech,
president of the New Jersey AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's no different than you negotiating a mortgage rate with
your bank,'' Wowkanech said. ''And all of a sudden the president of
the bank says, 'I'm not going to honor that deal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, there's evidence unions took on Whitman's ''smaller,
smarter government'' rhetoric through a series of battles with the
Legislature during her first term.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers allied with labor fought the governor over policies
that would have fired public workers and replaced them with private
companies. And last year, more than half the Legislature signed on
as co-sponsors of a bill that would prevent Whitman from
overhauling civil service rules.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric toned down during Whitman's second term, when
members of the administration cited concerns that the public
wouldn't support layoffs and cuts during a booming economy. In the
past year, Whitman has signed 15 bills that increased or restored
public employee benefits and signed none curtailing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman said Republicans should try again at reform, this
time with a new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Without offering a timetable or specifics, she suggested
presenting a limit on the payouts as a way to control New Jersey's
local property taxes, which are the highest in the nation. Any
Republican wanting to take her place could turn such reform into a
political gold mine in next year's election, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   But few lawmakers want to confront unions openly, although ''I
have seen data that says public employees are not particularly
popular,'' said Stephen Salmore, a Republican Party strategist.
</P>
<P>
   ''But no one is willing to take on the public employees and
remain confident that they can make up for those attacks with
broad-based support from the public,'' Salmore said. ''Politicians
are not risk takers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-28-00 1752 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000528.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies 11, Pirates 2  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Rolando Arrojo pitched seven innings for his first
victory in nearly seven weeks as the Colorado Rockies beat the
Pittsburgh Pirates 11-2 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin was 3-for-4 with three runs, and Mike Lansing
homered and had three RBIs for the Rockies, who improved to 16-6 at
Coors Field. Todd Helton went 3-for-4 to raise his major
league-leading average to .415.
</P>
<P>
   Looking nothing like the pitcher who had lost four straight
decisions, Arrojo (2-4) gave up two runs and six hits. He struck
out eight and walked one in his first victory since April 10, a
span of seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo's success came at the expense of Pittsburgh left-hander
Jimmy Anderson (1-3), who lasted just one inning. He gave up five
consecutive hits to start the game, and all five came around to
score.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing, who had an RBI triple in the first, gave the Rockies a
7-1 lead with a two-run homer off Josias Manzanillo in the fourth.
Colorado went ahead 9-1 before Brian Giles hit a solo homer, his
14th, for Pittsburgh in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates ended their road trip 1-5 and have lost seven of
eight.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Helton had reached base eight straight times before
grounding out in the third. He had five singles, two homers and a
walk in that stretch. ... Pirates C Jason Kendall went 3-for-4 to
extend his hitting streak to 13 games. He was 8-for-13 in the
series. ... Pittsburgh pinch hitters have one hit in their last 20
at-bats. Pirates leadoff hitters aren't faring much better, mired
in a 2-for-29 slump. ... Anderson has allowed a first-inning run in
six straight starts. He is 0-3 over that period. ... Colorado OF
Jeffrey Hammonds did not play Sunday after straining his left hip
flexor Saturday when he slammed into the wall in foul territory
along the first-base line. ... The Rockies got encouraging news
when OF Larry Walker threw for a second straight day as he recovers
from an elbow injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
