<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire in Edison condominium complex forces dozens to evacuate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EDISON, N.J. (AP) -- At least 60 people were evacuated in a
pre-dawn fire that destroyed three condominium buildings under
construction and damaged two others where people were living,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the 3:43 a.m. fire began in a unit under
construction, then wind blew embers to other homes in the Village
Point complex.
</P>
<P>
   One firefighter suffered smoke inhalation injuries, and a police
officer injured his back when he tried to kick in a door during the
evacuation, said Edison Police Lt. Robert Ellmyer, who also is the
community's Emergency Management Coordinator. One elderly woman was
sent to the hospital to be treated for dehydration, Ellmyer said.
</P>
<P>
   All three were treated at John F. Kennedy Medical Center in
Edison and released.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was under control by daybreak, but took most of Sunday
afternoon to extinguish entirely. Firefighters were still at the
three-year-old complex at 5:45 p.m., trying to douse hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   Three of four unoccupied buildings under construction were
destroyed. All 18 occupied condominiums in another building were
damaged, and a building with seven occupied units suffered minor
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross, Salvation Army and other emergency
groups helped in the evacuation. Most evacuees found temporary
housing on their own, but two families were helped to local hotels
by the Red Cross, Ellmyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the fire started in one of the buildings under
construction. The cause of the fire, considered suspicious, hadn't
been determined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
