<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Not Ruling Out Russia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- NATO Secretary-General George Robertson said in an
interview aired Sunday that he does not rule out Russia ultimately
joining the western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   After Russia-NATO talks in Italy on Thursday, Robertson told
Russian state television that Russia's inclusion in the alliance
could be debated ''in the next two decades'' but there were no
immediate plans to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Vladimir Putin, then acting Russian president, told
the British Broadcasting Corp. that Russia could join NATO ''if and
when Russia's views are taken into account as an equal partner.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My answer to the same question is 'Why not?''' Robertson said
in the Russian state TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   Russia-NATO ties were almost completely frozen last year over
NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia, which Russia strongly
opposed. Tensions were later aggravated by Western criticism of
Russia's war in breakaway Chechnya, but an agreement to restore
ties was announced in February when Robertson visited Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
