<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Top Franchise Value List  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- When it comes to money, the New York Yankees are
king of the hill, top of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes magazine said Sunday the Yankees are worth $548 million,
making the two-time defending World Series champions the most
valuable team in baseball for the third straight year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are worth more than six times as much as the least
valuable franchise in the survey, the Montreal Expos
</P>
<P>
   Second-highest among the 30 franchises is the Atlanta Braves at
$388 million, Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the list of the top 10 most valuable teams are
Cleveland ($364 million), Baltimore ($347 million), Los Angeles
($325 million), the New York Mets ($314 million), Colorado ($305
million), Texas ($294 million), Seattle ($290 million) and Boston
($284 million).
</P>
<P>
   The least valuable franchises are Montreal ($89 million),
Minnesota ($91 million), Kansas City ($122 million), Florida ($125
million), Oakland ($134 million) and Philadelphia ($150 million).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have baseball's highest payroll at $92.5 million,
more than the value of either the Expos or the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees made $17.5 million in operating income, the magazine
said, on revenue of $195.6 million. The only team that beat the
Yankees in operating income was the Braves at $18.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees owner George Steinbrenner led a group that paid $10
million to purchase the team from CBS in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner was in negotiations last year to sell the team to
Cablevision. But the deal fell apart when Cablevision chairman
Charles Dolan, brother of Indians owner Lawrence Dolan, wouldn't
allow Steinbrenner total control of the team.
</P>
<P>
   While the value of the Yankees increased 11 percent from 1999,
the biggest jump was recorded by Detroit. The Tigers, playing in
new Comerica Park, are worth $200 million, a one-year increase of
32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said 13 of the 30 teams had operating losses last year,
topped by the Los Angeles Dodgers at $21.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Brewers, owned by a trust established by Bud Selig
when he became commissioner, lost $14.4 million. Texas lost $9.5
million, San Francisco lost $9 million and San Diego lost $8.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1830 </TRAILER>
