<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Election Council Targeted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A government official in charge of
safeguarding citizens' rights said Sunday that voting authorities
should face questioning after Venezuela's national elections were
postponed.
</P>
<P>
   The National Election Council has come under enormous public
pressure to step down this week for failing to carry out the
election that had been set for Sunday, but was postponed due to
computer glitches and bad planning.
</P>
<P>
   But Dilia Parra, a top government official, promised to ask the
legislature not to allow the council to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ''This would mean continuing the vicious practice in Venezuela
that there are not severe sanctions for those who shamelessly
violate their oath to serve the country and later pretend to remedy
the situation by offering their resignation,'' Parra said in a
radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member council could face prosecution if found
responsible for the problems that led to the postponement of the
election in this South American country of 23 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the country's high court postponed the vote, citing
technical glitches. The legislature has not determined a new date
for balloting.
</P>
</TEXT>
