<HEADLINE> Blazers' Wallace Tries To Rally Team  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Rasheed Wallace tried to rally the
Portland Trail Blazers. Without any help from his teammates, he
didn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace scored 18 of his playoff career-high 34 points in the
fourth quarter, when the rest of the Blazers contributed just seven
points, as the Los Angeles Lakers pulled away for a 103-91 victory
Sunday and a 3-1 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace added 13 rebounds, also a postseason best. His previous
highs of 29 points and 12 rebounds came in Portland's Game 2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, playing on a sore left ankle, missed his first two
shots of the fourth but then scored the next 13 points for the
Blazers. His turnaround bank shot with 5:40 to play cut the lead to
89-79 -- the same margin the Lakers had to start the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers still had a chance to rally. But Wallace, never
known to demand the ball even when he has an advantage, somehow
disappeared in the Blazers' halfcourt offense.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he scored again -- on a dunk after twice grabbing his
own miss -- the Blazers trailed 99-82 with just under three minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Wallace was 6-for-12 from the field and 6-for-8
from the line. The rest of the Blazers took just 10 shots, making
three.
</P>
<P>
   The first Portland player to score other than Wallace was Steve
Smith, who hit one of two free throws with 5:06 left. Portland
didn't get a basket from another player until a meaningless dunk by
center Arvydas Sabonis with 2:15 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Blazers didn't fall behind for good until the
Lakers went on a 14-3 run in the third quarter, they were hurt
early by Sabonis' two first-quarter fouls. Sabonis hit two quick
jumpers, including a 3-pointer, to start the game, and Shaquille
O'Neal faced a long day of chasing the 7-foot-3 Lithuanian all over
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis played just eight minutes in the first half, however,
sitting out the entire second quarter. He came back with seven
points in the third, including a rousing baseline move on O'Neal
for a dunk and foul that cut the lead to 60-57 with 5:25 left.
</P>
<P>
   Portland got within 60-58, but Kobe Bryant's 3-pointer capped a
quick 9-2 run that ended another Blazers rally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1852 </TRAILER>
