<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plea Bargains Offered For Carruth  </HEADLINE>
By RANDALL CHASE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rae Carruth and three co-defendants have been offered a plea
bargain that could spare them possible death sentences, a source
familiar with the case told The Associated Press on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth's lawyer said the former Carolina Panthers player was
not interested in a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing that Rae Carruth is interested in is a speedy
trial to clear his name, a trial as soon as possible to clear his
name,'' defense attorney David Rudolf said.
</P>
<P>
   A source who has seen the plea offers made to Carruth and Van
Brett Watkins told The Associated Press on condition of anonymity
that lawyers for all the defendants had filed statements indicating
plea offers were received from the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The plea-bargain offerings were reported in the Sunday editions
of the Charlotte Observer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just not going to have anything to say about this story,''
assistant district attorney Gentry Caudill said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth and the other men are charged with first-degree murder
in the Nov. 16 shooting of Cherica Adams. Adams, Carruth's
girlfriend, who was gunned down while driving in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   She was pregnant with Carruth's child at the time. Doctors
delivered a boy by emergency Caesarean section hours after the
shooting. Adams died Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth, Watkins, Michael Eugene Kennedy and Stanley Drew
''Boss'' Abraham are charged with first-degree murder, which
carries a sentence of life in prison or the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Each defendant also is charged with conspiring to commit murder,
shooting into an occupied vehicle and using a gun to try to kill
Adams' unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   James Gronquist, a lawyer for Abraham, said state rules prohibit
him from discussing plea negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone messages for lawyers representing the other two
defendants were not immediately returned Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The plea offers call for different punishments based on the
defendants' alleged roles and criminal records, with Carruth facing
as much as 30 years in prison, the Observer reported.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth and Watkins, the accused triggerman, must both plead
guilty for their deals to be accepted by prosecutors, the newspaper
said. Watkins, who has a criminal record, would get the harshest
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Gronquist said such plea offers don't necessarily mean
prosecutors think they have a weak case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Plea offers are relatively routine, even in murder cases, in
our county,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf filed motions last week asking that Carruth's trial be
held on or before Nov. 15, one day before the anniversary of the
fatal shooting. He also wanted a timetable for prosecutors to turn
over discovery material.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still haven't gotten it all,'' Rudolf said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth has been held without bail since December. The other
defendants also have remained in custody, and no trial date has
been set.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are due in court Tuesday to discuss the discovery phase
and other issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1852 </TRAILER>
