<DOCNO> APW20000528.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Wins LPGA Corning Classic  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORNING, N.Y. (AP) -- Betsy King made a 10-foot birdie putt on
the second hole of sudden-death playoff with Kelli Kuehne and Vicki
Goetze-Ackerman on Sunday to win the LPGA Corning Classic for the
second time.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 33rd career victory for King and the eighth triumph
in 14 playoffs for the Hall of Famer. King, who won $120,000, also
won the 1991 Corning Classic after barely surviving the cut. It was
the fourth playoff in the tournament's 22 years and first involving
three players.
</P>
<P>
   This was Kuehne's tournament to win for the second straight
year. Instead, she lost it, giving away a two-shot lead with a
double-bogey on the tricky 377-yard, par-4 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Goetze-Ackerman, seeking her first tour victory, had a
final-round 67 to finish at 12-under 276. She was giving interviews
to the media when Kuehne's third shot on No. 18 landed in the deep
rough to the right of the green.
</P>
<P>
   When King made par and Kuehne's chip left her with a 12-foot
bogey putt that she missed, Goetze-Ackerman suddenly found herself
back in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   All three players parred the first extra hole, No. 18, and were
quickly whisked to the 345-yard No. 8, another par-4.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne's second shot nearly hit the pin but rolled about 30 feet
past the hole, while Goetze-Ackerman put her second shot within 12
feet -- birdie range.
</P>
<P>
   King, whose drive landed in the right rough, had to clear a tree
with her second shot and did, with her ball landing on the green
and glancing off Goetze-Ackerman's ball and stopping about 10 feet
from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne missed her birdie try as the ball broke right 2 feet.
After Goetze-Ackerman rimmed her birdie attempt out to the moans
and groans of the crowd, King then calmly holed hers, watching it
break about 8 inches as it rolled straight into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hurst, who had a closing 69, could have made it a four-way
playoff but bogeyed No. 18 when her second shot sailed over the
green into the gallery. She finished alone at 11-under 277.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Eathorne was fifth at 278 after a closing 68 and Leslie
Spalding was another stroke back in sixth. Liz Earley of Canada,
who got as low as 11 under with a birdie on No. 5, a 449-yard
par-5, faltered with three bogeys on the final 10 holes and
finished in a three-way tie for seventh with Emilee Klein and
Sherri Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne started the day with a one-shot lead over King, and the
two battled back and forth throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   A two-shot swing on the tough 412-yard, par-4 No. 13 put King
ahead by a stroke. Kuehne's drive had hit the right rough and she
two-putted for bogey from 35 feet while King drained a 20-foot putt
to go in front.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was King's turn to play giveaway. Leading by a stroke,
she hit her drive on the 304-yard 16th under a pine tree, and when
her wedge flew over the green she had bogey. Kuehne, on the green
in two, calmly sank a 20-foot putt for birdie and had the lead back
again.
</P>
<P>
   Goetze-Ackerman, who began the day four shots off the lead,
zoomed into contention with five birdies on the front nine, three
in a row. Her 67 tied Joan Pitcock for the best round of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
