<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Padres 4, Expos 3  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Al Martin drove in San Diego's first three
runs, and the go-ahead run scored when Montreal third baseman Andy
Tracy dropped a popup as the Padres rallied to beat the Expos 4-3
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who had been 2-for-32 with runners in scoring position
this year, hit an RBI double in the first and a two-run single in
the fifth. He added a triple in the seventh to finish 3-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, who fell behind 3-0 in the first inning, have won
four straight games for the first time since July 10-16, a streak
that spanned the All-Star break. The Expos have lost five straight.
</P>
<P>
   After Martin tied the game at three in the fifth, the Padres
scored the winning run without benefit of a hit in the sixth. They
got a walk, a fielder's choice, a hit batsman and two errors.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone reached when his grounder erased Ryan Klesko at
second for the second out. He then stole second, with an errant
throw by catcher Brian Schneider allowing him to take third. After
Ruben Rivera was hit by a pitch from Carl Pavano (5-2), Wiki
Gonzalez hit a popup. Tracy fought the sun but appeared to have a
bead on the ball, which popped out of his glove after Boone had
already crossed the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy's error was the third by the Expos and the fifth in the
game overall.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Walker (1-0) got his first big league win by pitching the
scoreless sixth, allowing one hit and one walk. Walker was promoted
from Triple-A Las Vegas on April 13. Trevor Hoffman pitched a
perfect ninth for his 11th save in 12 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Martin tied the game at 3 when he poked a two-run single just
over the outstretched glove of second baseman Jose Vidro. He was
thrown out trying to stretch it into a double to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Martin started the Padres' comeback with a first-inning double
to score Eric Owens, who hit a leadoff single and stole second.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos jumped on Padres starter Stan Spencer to take a 3-0
lead in the first inning. Lee Stevens hit a two-run homer with two
outs, a high shot to right, his 11th, and Rondell White drove in a
run with a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's slow delivery gives runners a great chance to steal,
and Peter Bergeron did just that after reading on a leadoff walk,
then advanced on Vidro's groundout and scoring on White's grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano allowed four runs -- three earned -- and six hits in seven
innings. Spencer, who struck out nine, allowed three runs and six
hits in five innings. He walked three.
</P>
<P>
   Padres third baseman Phil Nevin committed two errors in the span
of two batters in the sixth inning, but the Expos failed to
capitalize.
</P>
<P>
Notes: With starter Woody Williams on the DL and Sterling
Hitchcock likely headed there, the Padres are set for another round
of callups. RHP Adam Eaton, currently with Double-A Mobile, is
scheduled to make his major league debut on Tuesday and Rodrigo
Lopez is to be called up for the second time this season from
Triple-A Las Vegas to start Wednesday in Hitchcock's spot. ...
Hitchcock plans to seek a second opinion on the sprained ulnar
collateral ligament in his throwing elbow from Anaheim Angels Dr.
Lewis Yocum. ... Tony Gwynn, who raised his average from .186 to
.260 in eight games since coming off the disabled list, got Sunday
off.
</P>
</TEXT>
