<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressRichard P. Keirn
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Retired Col. Richard P. Keirn, a former Air
Force pilot who was held prisoner during World War II and the
Vietnam War, died Thursday. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Keirn was 20 when he was shot down over
Germany in 1944. He spent nine months as a German prisoner of war.
After the war, he became a member of the Ohio Air National Guard,
and returned to full-time duty in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, he was sent to Vietnam, and was shot down over Hanoi
while on his fifth mission.
</P>
<P>
   He was imprisoned by the North Vietnamese for more than seven
years. He was thought to be dead in 1965, but then newspaper
editors identified him from a wire service photo.
</P>
<P>
   Keirn earned several military honors, including the Silver Star
and Distinguished Flying Cross.
Milo A. Speriglio
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Milo A. Speriglio, a private detective who
looked into the deaths of celebrities such as ''Superman'' star
George Reeves and wrote three books claiming Marilyn Monroe was
murdered, died April 30 of lung cancer. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Sperilgio's career spanned 41 years, including three decades as
chief of Nick Harris Detectives, Inc., one of the nation's oldest
private detective agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Speriglio co-founded the California Association of
Licensed Investigators, described as the world's largest private
investigator association.
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio's cases were rarely high-profile. He traced missing
people, investigated frauds and cons and spied on unfaithful
spouses.
</P>
<P>
   But he did look into the 1959 shooting death of Reeves, who
played Superman on television in the 1950s. His mother disbelieved
the official verdict of suicide and hired the Nick Harris agency.
The agency's report concluded that two bullets were fired at Reeves
from at least 16 inches away.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Speriglio began investigating Monroe's death. In
three books, he laid out a hypothesis that the film star, who
officially died of a drug overdose in 1962, actually was killed by
a Mafia hit team on behalf of President Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio's probe led to the opening of police files on the
death and calls for a grand jury investigation. A censored version
of Monroe's FBI file was turned over to the Los Angeles County
district attorney's office, which concluded her death was either a
suicide or accidental and there was no need for further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, two daughters and a sister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-28-00 1949 </TRAILER>
