<DOCNO> APW20000528.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Coli Said Sickening Fewer Now  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALKERTON, Ontario (AP) -- Fewer people were getting sick from
one of North America's worst E. coli outbreaks, a health official
said Sunday, though one elderly victim was moved into a terminal
care unit and was expected to die.
</P>
<P>
   Five people have died so far and hundreds were sickened by E.
coli bacteria that contaminated the water supply in Walkerton, a
southern Ontario town of 5,000 people about 90 miles west of
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Waram, acting chief executive of the local South
Bruce-Grey Health Center, said the patient was moved to the
palliative care section.
</P>
<P>
   ''That usually means they don't want any acute care, any blood
tests, any invasive treatments, they want support,'' Waram said.
''They've accepted the fact that death is imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another 13 victims of the contamination that emerged after a
storm flooded the area on May 12 have been airlifted to the London,
Ontario, Health Sciences Centers. Eleven of the transported
patients were children, and five remained in critical condition
with kidney problems.
</P>
<P>
   Waram noted her hospital received 30 visits Sunday from people
complaining of E. coli symptoms, compared to 56 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''My sense is that the worst is over, certainly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in another Ontario community that was placed under a
boil order after traces of E. coli showed up in its water said the
problem appeared to be isolated and controlled. There was not
believed to be any connection between the bacteria detected in
Freelton and the Walkerton contamination 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks carrying bottled water moved through Walkerton on Sunday,
with volunteers carrying the donated cases to doorsteps in some
areas. Church services focused on forgiveness amid reports that the
local water utility knew of the problem as soon as May 18 but never
notified health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody messed up,'' the Rev. Suzanne Hollands told her
Anglican congregation. ''But we all make mistakes, even mistakes
that cause death. There is so much pain, but we know we all have to
stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   The intestinal bacteria, often spread through animal or human
feces, may have entered the town wells in flooding that followed
the May 12 storm. City officials have acknowledged the chlorinating
system on one of the town's two main wells had been malfunctioning
for weeks before people started getting sick.
</P>
<P>
   A provincial water agency has taken control of the local water
utility, and police, health and environmental officials are
investigating the contamination. At least one class-action lawsuit
has been filed on behalf of victims, but many residents say they
think seeking legal action is premature.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Palmateer of GAP EnviroMicrobial Services said his company
found another bacteria in the town's water supply as far back as
January. Palmateer said the finding showed surface water was
seeping into the town wells, and that he notified local and Ontario
officials about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Environment Ministry spokesman John Steele has confirmed the
ministry received similar test results in early May from a
different company.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa, Prime Minister Jean Chretien commended the people of
Walkerton for their courage.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to make sure that situations like that do not arrive
again in our country,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
