<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Might Cause Grand Prix Chaos  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- The city of Montreal faces a three-day traffic
nightmare during next month's Formula One Grand Prix weekend -- the
dates selected for a strike by public transit workers.
</P>
<P>
   The workers voted overwhelmingly Sunday in favor of the strike,
threatening to make life miserable for 115,000 spectators expected
at the track on Notre Dame Island, just outside the city center,
from June 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   Even with additional public transportation last year, traffic
backlogs for the event exceeded one hour at some times.
</P>
<P>
   About 98 percent of 2,000 unionized workers voted to pressure
the transit corporation into returning to the bargaining table
after contract negotiations broke down six weeks ago over employer
pension contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have gotten nowhere since the (corporation) ended
negotiations April 15,'' union president Gaetan Chateauneuf said.
''This is a first move to make a big impact on the employer without
affecting workday commuters as much.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether they will be allowed to strike during the Grand Prix
is up to Quebec's Essential Services Council.
</P>
<P>
   Neither buses nor the subway can run without the mechanics,
electricians and other workers responsible for ensuring the
maintenance and safety of the public transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   A previous agreement with drivers excluded public transit on
normal weekends from the list of essential services.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Odile Paradis, spokeswoman for the transit
corporation, the sheer number of people depending on the subway
makes Grand Prix weekend an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ''We transport 20,000 people per hour during the Grand Prix,''
Paradis said. ''Without a (subway), what's the solution? There are
no boats, no trains and access for cars is limited. The traffic
jams would be horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paradis was not so much concerned with spectators'
convenience as with their safety.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the event of an emergency, the (subway) is the only way to
evacuate the island and traffic jams would make it impossible for
fire trucks or ambulances to get through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse began in January when the transit corporation
announced it would stop paying the $30 million annual contribution
to employees' pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   The employer said the fund had more money than allowed by law
and wanted to use excess funds to improve the transit system,
triggering several protests and work slowdowns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
