<HEADLINE> Notes From Sunday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Red Sox-Yankees:
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON: Boston's bullpen anticipated an easy night with Pedro
Martinez starting. He had gone seven or more innings in all nine
starts this season. Opponents were batting .167 against him, lowest
average against any pitcher, and .054 with runners in scoring
position. ... Martinez's 1.19 ERA is a major part of Red Sox' 3.55
team ERA, which leads both leagues. Boston has not led the majors
in ERA since 1914.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: New York's bullpen leads majors with just four home
runs allowed. Yankees relievers also lead in ERA (2.71) and fewest
hits allowed (112). ... Outfielder-DH Felix Jose is close to being
reinstated from the disabled list. Jose went on the DL April 30,
his first day on the roster, with a strained left groin.
Mariners-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: After hitting first-inning leadoff homers in his
previous three starts against Tampa Bay, Rickey Henderson grounded
out to start Sunday's game. The Mariners' next hitter, Mike
Cameron, hit a solo homer off Albie Lopez. ... LHP Jamie Moyer,
sidelined since April 15 by a shoulder injury, reported no problems
after pitching a simulated game Saturday and is scheduled to start
Friday against San Diego. ... John Mabry, who allowed two runs and
three hits in two-thirds of an inning, joined infielder Manny
Castillo as the only Mariner position players to pitch in a game.
Castillo gave up seven runs and eight hits -- including three homers
-- over 2 2-3 innings on June 26, 1983 against Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: LF Greg Vaughn (strained right hamstring) was out of
the starting lineup for the second straight game. ''It's still sore
.. it's not an overnight thing,'' manager Larry Rothschild said.
''It's not going to be a quick decision to put him on the DL or not
because of what he means to this time.'' ... OF Randy Winn was
recalled from Triple-A Durham and batted leadoff. It was the first
time this season someone other than Gerald Williams, who batted
second, hit in that spot. ... OF Quinton McCracken was optioned to
Triple-A Durham. ... RHP Cory Lidle may get his first start of the
season Wednesday against Baltimore.
Blue Jays-Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays have not lost a season series to Detroit
since 1995. Last season they were 10-2 against the Tigers, their
second-best year ever against Detroit, topped only by an 11-2 mark
in 1989. The Blue Jays have 154 wins over Detroit in their history,
the most over any AL opponent. They have 150 wins over Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: 1B Tony Clark, on the DL since May 13 with a strained
left rib cage, has started swinging a bat again. He hit off a tee
Sunday and planned to take some swings against soft toss on Monday.
Clark said he might try some live batting practice Tuesday.
Rangers-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers allowed 20 runs in the first two games of the
series against the Twins, the most given up in a two-game span
since surrendering 26 against Oakland on May 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Coco and Kelly Miller, twins from Rochester, Minn.,
who played together on the Georgia women's basketball team, were
part of ''Twins Day'' at the Metrodome. About 500 sets of twins
were expected to attend the game. ... The Twins, who had won only
four season series from the Rangers in the last 12 years, have
already won both series from Texas this season.
Indians-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Manager Charlie Manuel said RHP Jim Brower will start
Monday at home against Anaheim. Brower gets the call in place of
Paul Rigdon, who went on the disabled list Saturday with a strained
left oblique muscle. ... RHP Sean DePaula will be examined Monday
by doctors to see why he's had lingering arm pain since spring
training. ... The Indians currently have five pitchers on the
disabled list and have made 16 roster moves in the last 11 days.
''Every since day one of the season, we've never been able to get
out five-man rotation going,'' Manuel said. ''We've never got it
set. Once we get it organized and set, we can beat anybody in our
division.'' ... The Indians stole a season-high four bases Sunday
and avoided their first sweep by the White Sox since 1995. ... Omar
Vizquel stole a base Sunday and is now tied with Elmer Flick for
fifth in Indian history with 207. ... Robbie Alomar played Sunday
despite a painful sprained left wrist that he had X-rayed Sunday
morning. Alomar had a pair of RBI doubles and made a nice stop on a
hard-hit grounder by Chris Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: There's a fungus in the infield. That's the story at
Comiskey Park, where the grounds crew began removing the grass
immediately after Sunday's game with Cleveland had ended. Because
there have been so many rainy days and the field had to be covered
by a tarp so often, a fungus developed ... First baseman Paul
Konerko missed the entire Indians series after fouling a pitch off
his foot Thursday. Konerko was in so much pain that he had a second
X-ray taken. It revealed no break just a deep bone bruise. Konerko
was able to take 75 swings in the batting cage Sunday.
Athletics-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: The Athletics expect to play Sunday's rainout as part
of a doubleheader in September, giving them 18 games over a 17-day
period. ''The fact that it's in September makes it easier to take
because we'll have expanded rosters by then,'' assistant GM Paul
DePodesta said. ... Omar Olivares, the scheduled starter Sunday,
will pitch against the Yankees on Monday. It might be a good thing,
given that the right-hander is 2-4 lifetime against Baltimore,
including 0-1 this season. ... Sunday's washout left Oakland with a
split of the two-game series. The A's are 5-1-2 in road series this
year.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Injured catcher Charles Johnson got a free day of
rest and hopes to return to the lineup Monday. He hasn't played
since being hit in the groin with a foul ball on Friday night. ...
Baltimore finished the homestand 4-1. ... Despite their 21-26
record, the Orioles are still three games better than last year
after 47 games under former manager Ray Miller. ... Pat Rapp,
slated to pitch Sunday before the game was called by rain, will
face Tampa Bay on Monday night. ... The Orioles have given up 35
homers in May, allowing at least one homer in 19 of 23 games.
Angels-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The last time the Angels hit three straight home runs
was at Boston on April 24, 1984, when Reggie Jackson, Bobby Grich
and Brian Downing all went deep. Sunday's victory allowed the
Angels to avoid their first three-game losing streak of the season.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: These last six games marked the only time the
Royals will play at home in a 32-day stretch from May 8-June 8. ...
After the game the Royals designated LHP Paul Spoljaric for
assignment and brought up C Gregg Zaun from Triple-A Omaha.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Braves-Astros
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Fans weren't the only ones who appreciated Enron
Field's roof being closed for their air-conditioned comfort for the
second straight day Sunday. ''I like it closed better,'' Braves
third baseman Chipper Jones said. ''There is a lot of wind that
comes in here and swirls around with the roof open. That makes a
difference, not to mention the heat and humidity. It's better for
the fans. They deserve to watch the game in comfort.'' Gametime
temperature Sunday was 83 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Tal's Hill, the 30-degree hill that slopes up to the
center field wall at Enron Field, isn't getting good early reviews
from visiting teams. Atlanta's Andruw Jones had to make consecutive
climbs in Friday's game on long fly balls. Astros president Tal
Smith, for whom the hill is named, thinks it will catch on. ''I
think as players become familiar with it they'll adjust and do just
fine,'' Smith said. ''They got used to the hills at Crosley Field
and at Fenway and those hills were steeper than ours. It was
unusual that Andruw had to make two runs in a row, but he'll get
used to it.''
Pirates-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: C Jason Kendall went 3-for-4 Sunday to extend his
hitting streak to 13 games. He was 8-for-13 in the series. ...
Pittsburgh pinch-hitters have one hit in their last 20 at-bats.
Pirates leadoff hitters aren't faring much better, mired in a
2-for-29 slump. ... First-inning woes continued for LHP Jimmy
Anderson. He gave up five runs and five hits against Colorado and
has allowed at least one first-inning run in six straight starts.
He is 0-3 over that period and manager Gene Lamont said he will be
skipped in the starting rotation. ... OF Brian Giles hit a solo
homer that was caught by a fan just beyond the center field fence.
Rockies center fielder Tom Goodwin nearly made the catch but
admitted he probably did not have a chance regardless of the fan's
action. ''He kept apologizing to me every inning,'' Goodwin said.
''I was like, 'Don't worry about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: OF Jeffrey Hammonds did not play Sunday after
straining his left hip flexor Saturday when he slammed into the
wall in foul territory along the first-base line. ... The Rockies
got encouraging news when OF Larry Walker threw for a second
straight day as he recovers from an elbow injury. ... LHP Scott
Karl was demoted to the bullpen after a third straight shaky start.
The Rockies will use a four-man rotation until June 6, when LHP
Brian Bohanon likely will start at Seattle. ... Colorado has held
its opponents to less than 10 runs in 12 straight home games, the
longest such streak since going 13 games from July 10-12, 1998.
Mets-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Monday's expected starter, Al Leiter, is 5-0 with a
3.31 ERA. He has struck out 33 batters in his last 31 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Ray Lankford needs one walk to tie Rogers Hornsby for
sixth on the Cardinals all-time list with 660. He's two home runs
away from Hornsby (193) for third on the team career home run list.
... The Cardinals go on the road Monday, opening a four-game series
against Arizona. St. Louis then returns to Busch Stadium for the
start of interleague play. ... Garrett Stephenson (7-0) is the
expected starter Monday against the Diamondbacks. He's getting the
highest run support, 5.8 per game, of any of St. Louis' five
starters.
Marlins-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Cliff Floyd has reached base in a career-high 26
consecutive games. ... Luis Castillo stole second and third after
leading off the third inning with a single, and added No. 22 in the
seventh by stealing second. Castillo has failed to reach base only
once in 33 games.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Former Braves closer Mark Wohlers is scheduled to
begin a minor league rehab assignment by pitching one inning Monday
for the Reds' Triple-A affiliate in Dayton. Wohlers tore a ligament
in his right elbow and had reconstructive surgery last July. ...
About 3,500 fans came to Cinergy Field early for Camera Day, when
they were allowed to go onto the field to snap photos of Reds
players up close.
Phillies-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Left-hander Randy Wolf's start on Sunday marked
his first appearance at Dodger Stadium since his final high school
game in 1994, when he pitched a complete game victory for El Camino
Real in the L.A. City Championship game and earned MVP honors. The
native of Canoga Park, Calif. might have been a tad nervous -- he
hit his first batter, F.P. Santangelo, with his second pitch. ...
The Phillies, who have scored fewer runs than any team except the
Detroit Tigers, left the bases twice on Sunday. They have stranded
three baserunners 14 times this season. ... Ron Gant ended an
0-for-16 drought Sunday with a third-inning double against Carlos
Perez. ...
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: 3B Adrian Beltre, who strained his right hamstring
running out a grounder to second base in Saturday night's 7-6 loss,
will be placed on the 15-day disabled list Monday, retroactive to
Sunday. Dave Hansen and Jose Vizcaino will fill in until the
three-year veteran returns from his first trip to the DL. ...
Former Brooklyn Dodgers Cy Young winner Don Newcombe, now the
team's director of community relations, said Sunday that his
reaction to a teammate being assaulted by a fan in the stands would
have been no different than that of Chad Kreuter's in Chicago on
May 16. ''There's no doubt about it. I'd be right in the middle of
it, if it happened when I played,'' Newcombe said. ''I would have
gone in there to protect my teammate -- but you also have to be a
peacemaker. I remember one day locking my arms around Don Drysdale
one day in Brooklyn because I wanted to keep him out of trouble.''
Expos-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Four Expos have at least 35 RBIs and are on pace to
drive in more than 100, which would be a franchise first. They are
Vladimir Guerrero, who leads the team with 40, followed Rondell
White (39), Lee Stevens (38) and Jose Vidro. White had an RBI
groundout in the first inning Sunday against San Diego and White a
two-run homer. There have never been two Expos reach the 100-RBI
mark in the same year. Guerrero had 131 RBIs last year.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: LHP Sterling Hitchcock plans to seek a second opinion
on his injured pitching elbow from Anaheim Angels Dr. Lewis Yocum.
Hitchcock left Friday night's game with a sprained ulnar collateral
ligament. Hitchcock has said he'll need exploratory surgery. Sugary
is an option, assistant trainer Jim Daniel said Sunday, but a
decision hasn't been made yet. Hitchcock likely will go on the
disabled list. ... Tony Gwynn, who's gotten his average up from
.186 to .260 in eight games since coming off the disabled list, got
Sunday off. ... Chris Gomez started at SS Sunday after Damian
Jackson jammed the pinkie on his glove hand diving for a ball
Saturday night. Manager Bruce Bochy said Jackson might be out for a
few days.
Brewers-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Jeromy Burnitz was hitless in 10 straight at-bats
before singling in the fourth. He later homered, too.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Tony Womack extended his hitting streak to 23 games,
the longest in the majors this season.
Cubs-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Sammy Sosa has now homered in 32 different major league
ballparks. ... The Cubs last won a road series when they took two
of three at Houston on April 25-27.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: The Giants' 4-1 loss Sunday marked just their
fourth defeat in the past 16 games at Pacific Bell Park. ... Losing
pitcher Kirk Rueter had his second-shortest outing of the season,
going five innings. Although he lowered his home ERA to 3.23, he
fell to 0-3 in six starts at home.
</P>
