<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, May 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Weather May Delay Shuttle Landing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP)-- Despite forecasts calling for gusty wind, space
shuttle Atlantis' astronauts aimed for an early Monday morning touchdown to
close out their successful space station repair mission. It will be only the
14th time in 98 flights that a space shuttle lands in darkness. ''I've been
practicing for this for the last 10 years,'' said Air Force Col. James Halsell
Jr., Atlantis' commander. ''It's going to be just another of the great parts of
this adventure.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NATO Chief Not Ruling Out Russia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- NATO Secretary-General George Robertson said in an interview
aired Sunday that he does not rule out Russia ultimately joining the western
alliance. After Russia-NATO talks in Italy on Thursday, Robertson told Russian
state television that Russia's inclusion in the alliance could be debated ''in
the next two decades'' but there were no immediate plans to discuss the issue.
In March, Vladimir Putin, then acting Russian president, told the British
Broadcasting Corp. that Russia could join NATO ''if and when Russia's views are
taken into account as an equal partner.'' ''My answer to the same question is
'Why not?''' Robertson said in the Russian state TV interview.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fujimori Appears Headed for Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Alberto Fujimori on Sunday appeared headed for a third
term as Peru's president, with poll projections giving him a wide lead in
elections boycotted by his rival and characterized as tainted by foreign
monitors. The first independent vote projection gave Fujimori a large lead over
challenger Alejandro Toledo, but said 30.6 percent of the ballots had been
annulled. Fujimori led with 49.6 percent of the ballot to 15 percent for Toledo
with an additional 4.8 percent of the ballots left blank, according to the
respected polling firm CPI.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Costly Fuel Forces Coast Guard Cuts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEABROOK, Texas (AP) -- All along the Texas coast and into the Midwest,
rising fuel costs have forced the Coast Guard to cut back nearly every type of
patrol but search-and-rescue missions by about 25 percent, officials said. ''I
had no other recourse,'' said Rear Adm. Paul Pluta, whose Eighth Coast Guard
District covers 26 states and includes 1,200 miles of Gulf Coast and 10,300
miles of navigable rivers. Oil prices have increased dramatically in recent
months, reaching $34 a barrel in March, almost $10 higher than in January.
Prices were down to about $28 a barrel this month, but the Coast Guard still
needs more money to make up for higher costs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
2 Missing in Alaska Avalanche
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Two climbers were missing today after an avalanche
on Mount Foraker in Denali National Park and Preserve. National Park Service
spokeswoman Jane Tranel said another team of climbers witnessed a mass of ice
give way and heard screams and shouts at about the 8,000-foot level of the
mountain early this morning. The two missing climbers, whose names have not been
released, were going up a route known as the Infinite Spur, a steep route of ice
and rock.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S. Leone Rebels Release U.N. Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leonean rebels on Sunday freed what
appeared to be the last of some 500 U.N. hostages seized earlier this month,
signaling ''a positive change of direction'' among the rebels toward bringing
peace to the war-torn West African nation, a U.N. spokesman said. Eighty-five
former captives arrived in Freetown Sunday night from Monrovia, the capital of
neighboring Liberia, said U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst. A senior Liberian
military official who spoke on condition he not be named said more freed
hostages were still on the Sierra Leone-Liberia border and would be flown out on
Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks edged up in early trading Monday as investors
hunted for bargains following a recent decline in share prices. The Nikkei rose
153.04 points, or 0.96 percent, to 16,161.18 points in the first 30 minutes of
morning trading. Prices were higher as investors snapped up underpriced issues
following recent declines. But investors were expected to begin selling shares
before the Nikkei 225 reaches 16,300 because of growing concern over U.S.
stocks, particularly U.S. technology shares.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Juan Montoya Wins Indy 500
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Juan Montoya made a dominating detour from auto racing's
civil war today with an Indianapolis 500 victory that was the strongest case yet
for which side is best. Montoya, the defending champion of the more established
Championship Auto Racing Teams series, made car owner Chip Ganassi's decision to
return to Indy after a four-year absence look brilliant. The 24-year-old
Colombian fended off a late challenge from 1996 Indy winner Buddy Lazier, passed
teammate Jimmy Vasser to retake the lead 21 laps from the end and raced on to
become the first Indianapolis rookie to win since Graham Hill in 1966.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
