<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, May 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fujimori Appears Headed for Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori appeared headed Sunday for a
lopsided re-election victory in a runoff poll questioned by foreign observers
and boycotted by his opponent. With 26.9 percent of the vote counted, Fujimori
had 50.1 percent of the ballot to Alejandro Toledo's 16.5 percent, election
officials said. They said 32.4 percent of the ballots had been spoiled and 1
percent left blank. Toledo had originally urged Peruvians to boycott the runoff
election, forced after Fujimori failed to get a majority in the first round. But
voting is compulsory, and he later told them to spoil their ballots by scrawling
on them the words, ''no to fraud.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Reps, Farmers Visit Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Lawmakers and rice farmers from Arkansas began a trip to Cuba
today aimed at making agricultural contacts on this communist island and showing
support for a partial lifting of a U.S. trade embargo. ''We're anxious to see
how we can provide products and open up trade with Cuba,'' U.S. Sen. Blanche
Lambert Lincoln, a Democrat, said upon arriving tonight in Havana. ''We want to
know how we can help our economy, but also how that might benefit the Cuban
people.'' The visit of the 16-member delegation comes as the House of
Representatives debates legislation that would allow food and medicine to be
sold to Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
French Premier Opens Monetary Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin opened an international
monetary conference Sunday reiterating his confidence in the euro, saying the
currency has ''definitively'' created a new business environment for Europe. The
conference, which closes Wednesday, brings together the heads of the world's
main central banks, including U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan,
European Central Bank chief Wim Duisenberg, the heads of Germany's Bundesbank
and the Bank of Japan and Bank of France Governor Jean-Claude Trichet.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Weather May Delay Shuttle Landing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP)-- Despite forecasts calling for gusty wind, space
shuttle Atlantis' astronauts aimed for an early Monday morning touchdown to
close out their successful space station repair mission. It will be only the
14th time in 98 flights that a space shuttle lands in darkness. ''I've been
practicing for this for the last 10 years,'' said Air Force Col. James Halsell
Jr., Atlantis' commander. ''It's going to be just another of the great parts of
this adventure.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NATO Chief Not Ruling Out Russia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- NATO Secretary-General George Robertson said in an interview
aired Sunday that he does not rule out Russia ultimately joining the western
alliance. After Russia-NATO talks in Italy on Thursday, Robertson told Russian
state television that Russia's inclusion in the alliance could be debated ''in
the next two decades'' but there were no immediate plans to discuss the issue.
In March, Vladimir Putin, then acting Russian president, told the British
Broadcasting Corp. that Russia could join NATO ''if and when Russia's views are
taken into account as an equal partner.'' ''My answer to the same question is
'Why not?''' Robertson said in the Russian state TV interview.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Deutsche Post Adds E-Mail Delivery
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Looking for ways to keep from losing its business to
cyberspace, the German postal system is planning to offer e-mail services to
customers with and without Internet access. In an interview published in
Sunday's Bild am Sonntag newspaper, Deutsche Post chairman Klaus Zumwinkel said
they would begin offering free e-mail addresses to private customers by the end
of June.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks edged up in early trading Monday as investors
hunted for bargains following a recent decline in share prices. The Nikkei rose
153.04 points, or 0.96 percent, to 16,161.18 points in the first 30 minutes of
morning trading. Prices were higher as investors snapped up underpriced issues
following recent declines. But investors were expected to begin selling shares
before the Nikkei 225 reaches 16,300 because of growing concern over U.S.
stocks, particularly U.S. technology shares.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks' Sprewell Has Injured Foot
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- More bad news arrived today for the New York Knicks: Latrell
Sprewell has a foot injury that could keep him out of Game 4 of the Eastern
Conference finals. ''It's pretty stiff. It hurts,'' Sprewell said today as his
name was added to the Knicks' rapidly growing list of injured players. Sprewell
has a fractured fifth metatarsal, the bone behind the little toe on his left
foot. Patrick Ewing missed New York's 98-95 victory yesterday with acute
tendinitis in his foot, and Marcus Camby went down with a knee sprain.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
